<HEAD>Secretary of State Sees Breakthrough in Bases Impasse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Two grafs SUB for grafs 6-7 pvs, He left ... UPDATING with
Shultz arriving in Hong Kong. PICKS up 8th graf pvs, House speaker
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>BY DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> indicated Tuesday that he and Philippine leaders have scored a breakthrough in stalled talks on the future of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said after Tuesday's discussions, `` We both hope that the talks would be over by the end of this month.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told a news conference, `` I'm more than ever convinced that there is a very strong mutuality of interest in the security field and all the reason in the world that somehow we'll be able to work out a continuing partnership.'' A review of the 41-year-old bases agreement, which expires in 1991, has been marked by calls from some people for more compensation from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and by demonstrations against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military presence. The review began in April and stalled over the issue of how much <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> should pay each year for the <ORGANIZATION> Subic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Air </PERSON> <PERSON> Base </PERSON> and four smaller military installations. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, on a 36-hour visit to <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, met with Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, Foreign Secretary <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> and prominent legislators. He later left for <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, arriving there Wednesday for a one-day stay. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> was the fifth stop on the secretary's nine-nation Asian and Pacific tour He earlier visited <LOCATION