<HEAD>Taiwan Eases Ban on Travel From China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The governing <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday eased a 39-year-old ban on visits to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> by mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> residents and approved expanding indirect trade with <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to include raw materials. The new policy toward rival Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> approved by the 13th <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> congress </ORGANIZATION> after several days of debate also suggested <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> journalists and athletes may be allowed to go the mainland. Under the new policy, the <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, or Kuomintang, will review requests from mainland Chinese to travel to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> if close relatives are gravely ill or die. Intellectuals from mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> `` who are opposed to Marxism-Leninism or have fought to maintain academic freedom'' will be allowed to come to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> if invited. Further relaxation will depend on `` whether and how the mainland responds to our new policy,'' <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON> <PERSON> Chang-le </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Nationalists </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mainland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, told a news conference. Last October, the Nationalists ended a longstanding ban on travel to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> so <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> residents could visit relatives for family reunions. More than 100,000 have made the trip since. The ban on travel across the <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Straits </LOCATION> was imposed when the Nationalists fled to this island in 1949 after losing a civil war to the Communists on the Chinese mainland. The Nationalists government still claims to be the rightful ruler of all <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and refuses all official contact with <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON> said that also under the new policy, mainland Chinese students studying in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> can apply to visit <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> through an unidentified private organization beginning in August or September. He said <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> athletes may be allowed to compete on mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in events sponsored by private organizations and said the island's Olympic committee would study the possibility of sending a team to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> for the 1990 Asian Games. The party statement also indicated reporters may soon be allowed to travel to the mainland for news-gathering, but did not propose relax other travel restrictions opposed by many Taiwanese. Although no direct trade links exist between <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the Nationalists tolerate a flourishing trade through third countries that could reach a record $ 2 billion this year. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> government officials last year announced 29 items could be imported from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> indirectly but the list did not include raw materials and agricultural products now to be tolerated.
