<HEAD>South Korea Proposes Resumption Of Family-Reunion Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> called on communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> Wednesday to resume humanitarian programs to promote reunions between some 10 million people separated from their families on this divided peninsula. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sang-hyup </PERSON>, president of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, made the proposal in a telephone message to his North Korean counterpart <PERSON> Son </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON> <PERSON> Pil </PERSON>. `` In view of the ardent aspirations of separated family members, it is our imperative task to find out the whereabouts of their dispersed family members and relatives and help them to meet freely,'' <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> said in the message. <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> was divided into the Soviet-backed north and U.S.-supported south at the end of World War II. It is estimated that at least 10 million people were separated from their relatives by the division and during the Korean War in 1950-53. In his message, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> proposed the two Koreas resume by the end of the year a family-reunion program suspended since 1986. His appeal followed a statement Thursday by President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON> who called for improved relations with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, including broad exchanges of visits between people of the two countries. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> dismissed <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>'s gestures as `` nothing new'' and renewed its own demand for holding a `` national conference'' to discuss, among other things, co-hosting of this summer's Olympic Games in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and the withdrawal of 42,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Under the North Korean plan, the conference would be attended by about 50 government officials as well as social, political and cultural leaders from each side. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> specifically proposed that the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> societies of the two Koreas serve as an intermediary to help elderly people contact each other. His office said the program could be extended to include some one million overseas Koreans who want to locate relatives in the two Koreas through the Geneva-based <ORGANIZATION> Interantional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>. In 1985, for the first time in 40 years, the two governments agreed to an exchange involving 151 people. The agreement also included visits by cultural groups and 51 journalists. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> withdrew from the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> contacts and economic and parliamentary talks in 1986 to protest joint <LOCATION> U.S.-South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> military exercises.
