<HEAD>22nd Season Opens With Gala Concert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mostly <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON> was Mostly Marvelous. The 22nd season of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s alliterative summer musical festival opened Tuesday night with a gala concert featuring not one, but two, superstar soloists _ American mezzo-soprano <PERSON> Frederica </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Stade </PERSON> and Soviet emigre pianist <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Feltsman </PERSON>. Both made strong impressions. Miss <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Stade </PERSON> sang `` Parto, parto,'' an aria from <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON>'s last opera, `` La Clemenza di Tito'' and both of <PERSON> Cherubino </PERSON>'s arias from `` Le Nozze di <PERSON> Figaro </PERSON>.'' She sounded at ease in all three, her tone aristocratic, yet free and unaffected. Her technique was flawless in the difficult runs of the first selection, with only a hint of strain in the highest part of her register. <PERSON> Cherubino </PERSON> is perhaps <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Stade </PERSON>'s most famous role on stage and she demonstrated why, communicating the restless energy of a lovesick young boy with simple directness. <PERSON> Feltsman </PERSON>, who arrived in this country just last year, provided an elegant performance of <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON>'s last piano concerto, No. 27 in B-flat major. This work, written less than a year before the composer died, strikes a mood of serenity and triumph with little of the turmoil and tragedy that mark the concertos preceding it. <PERSON> Feltsman </PERSON> played with grace and clarity. Ironically, the least satisfying selection of the night was a collaboration between the two _ the concert aria for soprano, piano and orchestra `` Ch ` io mi scordi di te which <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON> wrote for an 18-year-old English singer with whom he had fallen in love. What sets this difficult aria apart is the intricate interplay between the female voice and the piano, each seeming to address the other in long, loving phrases. Miss <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Stade </PERSON> and <PERSON> Feltsman </PERSON> missed the emotional spark and too often seemed to be going through their paces rather than communicating. The opening program _ which is being repeated tonight and televised live on the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> _ was true to the title: mostly <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON>, but with a little something else thrown in. Conductor <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> led a spirited performance of <PERSON> Haydn </PERSON>'s grand and humorous Symphony No 100, known as the `` Military'' symphony. The concert opened with the overture to <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON>'s opera `` Die Entfuhrung aus dem Serail.'' It all went to show once again that <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON>, who died in poverty in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> at the age of 35, left behind a unique and inexhaustible supply of musical riches. What other composer could serve as the mainstay of a music festival that puts on concerts for seven weeks year after year? Highlights of the current season, performed in <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Avery </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, include <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON>'s rarely heard early opera `` <PERSON> Lucia </PERSON> <PERSON> Silla </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Haydn </PERSON>'s `` Lord Nelson'' Mass, and a chamber concert devoted entirely to <PERSON> Schubert </PERSON>
