<HEAD>25 Injured In Running Of The Bulls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAMPLONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Six youths were gored seriously and at least 19 others suffered minor injuries in the seventh and most dangerous running of the bulls at the San Fermin Festival. The six bulls and a group of lead steers ran the half-mile stretch from the corrals to the bull ring in less than eight minutes Tuesday, with more than 1,000 youths running ahead. The running took a dangerous turn when one bull stopped and began attacking several youths who had taken refuge in doorways and against the wooden planks lining the route. Every afternoon, the bulls are killed in professional bullfights. The festival began last Wednesday and is to continue through Thursday. Held continously since 1591, the festival gained fame when <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> used it as a setting for his 1926 novel, `` The Sun Also Rises.'' Since 1591, bulls have gored 52 people to death, 12 since 1924, according to official records.
</TEXT>
