<HEAD>Price Hikes Commonplace As Democrats Converge On Atlanta</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With hot water going for nearly $ 27 a gallon and potted plants renting for $ 79.50, there is money to be made at next week's Democratic National Convention. The days when delegates pulled into town with a $ 10 bill and a clean shirt and left without changing either are history. The 35,000 visitors for the July 18-21 event are expected to leave about $ 30 million in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. But some local plans to partake of the windfall have gone awry. An employee of an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> office furniture and equipment rental firm told one caller his company and many others like it had raised prices 30 to 40 percent in anticipation of the convention rush. So many news organizations and some <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> groups flocked to a Detroit-area firm willing to deliver, install, maintain and remove typewriters, computers, copiers, telefax machines and office furniture at roughly half the going <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> cost. For example, water coolers were quoted locally at $ 30 a day. The Detroit firm provides them at $ 30 a month. Some <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> companies are renting typing tables at $ 50 each, waste baskets for up to $ 27 and chairs for as much as $ 40. Convention Florist Service Int' l. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> lists the rental price on 7-foot green plant at $ 79.50. Local florists checked by telephone offered to sell similar plants outright for from $ 45 to $ 65. Hotels are also looking at a boom, with rooms for delegates, reporters, VIPs, fund-raisers, lobbyists, protesters and the curious at a premium. A prospectus for a major textile convention coming to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> in September lists a single room at the <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> at $ 102. A reservations clerk quoted a rate of $ 135 for the Democratic convention. A spot check found some hotels charging higher rates although some quoted rates at or below the rate being charged at the September textile convention. Many of the receptions, news conferences and hospitality rooms scheduled for the convention will be held at the <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, home base for most of the 12,000 news media representatives plus the party faithful who can not fit into the convention hall. <ORGANIZATION> MGR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the food service contractor for all events there, will cater about 950 convention functions over four days, from small hospitality suites to a windup `` victory party'' for 30,000. MGR president <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> Noyes </PERSON> said the company is hiring about 500 extra employees to handle the rush. However, the prices have been in effect for a year. `` We are n't the cheapest in the country,'' he acknowledged. `` We provide a highly specialized service and people pay for that. Our business is n't any different. People want a product that's iced down, chilled and ready, and all that goes with it.'' Last year a poll of 500 trade shows and conventions picked MGR as the best convention catering firm in the country. MGR will provide soft drinks at about $ 43 a case. Most meals will be served buffet-style with lunch at $ 14.50 and dinner at $ 18.50. Coffee, or hot water to make tea or instant coffee, is about $ 27 a gallon after tax and a 17 percent service charge are added. Fruit juice will be about $ 29 a gallon. Convention tenants are barred from having their own coffee makers. `` They're charging $ 165 for 100 little pieces of chicken. Everybody is complaining,'' said <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Yolanda </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroway </PERSON>. `` Prices have not been raised at all,'' said <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sterns </PERSON>, who oversees convention catering for the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. He said <ORGANIZATION> DNC </ORGANIZATION> surveys showed the prices to be lower than those at many downtown hotels. `` They have been very accommodating,'' he said when asked about the price of MGR's coffee service. `` They put in a program where the initial service is $ 50 and they provide a coffee maker. Each day they will deliver supplies at a lower rate for people who want to make their own coffee. They have made some concessions in that way.'' Delegates may get a break, however, if they come down with toothaches. An <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> dentist, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>, is offering free emergency dental service to delegates during the convention.
