<HEAD>Reagan Promises To Consider Lawmakers' Opposition To Seabrook
Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has promised to weigh opposition to a proposed executive order that could help license the <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, nuclear power plant by circumventing the objections of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Lawmakers from the all-Republican <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> congressional delegation, upset over the proposed federal intervention, said they received the pledge Monday after a White House briefing with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. `` We found the president very positive, very sympathetic, very understanding,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION> `` It was clear to all of us that the president was going to very actively consider our request that this order never be published.'' <PERSON> Rudman </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>, expressed optimism that the president may reject the proposal. `` I am very hopeful that this visit has an effect on the president in convincing him that the process was working -LRB- and -RRB- the federal government need not become involved at this time,'' <PERSON> Rudman </PERSON> told reporters outside the White House. <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> added, `` The president did n't say yes or no, but I came away more encouraged about our prospects of blocking this order than frankly I had expected to.'' But Rep. <PERSON> Judd </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>, who said before the briefing that he thought it would be extremely difficult to derail the proposal, said afterwards that he felt no more optimistic about the lawmakers' chances. `` He gave us no reading at all as to what his decision would be,'' said <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON>, noting that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> reiterated his strong support for atomic power and expressed concern over state governments' ability to block reactor licenses `` The president has not made a decision,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION> `` He will weigh our evidence and our advice. That's the best we can hope for at this time. The four lawmakers, loyal and long-time allies of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, have expressed support for plant licensing as long as federal regulators determine that the plant and evacuation plan are safe. Licensing for the <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> reactor has been stalled largely by the refusal of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to submit evacuation plans for the six <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> communities that fall within the plant's 10-mile emergency zone. The proposed executive order would give the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, which has served a strictly advisory role in atomic safety issues, the power to design and implement evacuation plans when local governments refuse to do so. The four were infuriated last month when they learned of the proposal through plant opponents, who discovered a draft and leaked it to reporters. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told the delegation that he had not seen any draft of the proposal, which sources said was initiated by the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, pushed by four senators and approved unanimously by the president's <ORGANIZATION> Domestic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and other plant opponents have said it is impossible to evacuate the area quickly and safely because of narrow rural roads and a large summertime population.
