normal, picking up 3rd graf pvs, `Woodfork said...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State troopers patrolled city streets Monday to make up for an apparent sick-out by more than 300 officers upset over low wages and the lack of a labor contract. The job action ended at late evening. Police Chief <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodfork </PERSON> said city streets were probably safer than usual because of the 60 troopers in the city. There were 143 officers and troopers on patrol, compared with a usual 83, police said. Officers began straggling back to work for the start of their late-evening shift, said police department spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryson </PERSON>. `` They have returned to work. We're back up to normal strength,'' he said. <PERSON> Woodfork </PERSON> said his department could continue to maintain security in the city of 500,000 even if police union members carry out a threat to stop work during next month's Republican National Convention. About 130 troopers already are scheduled to be in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> next month during the GOP convention. The sick-out began Sunday night and <PERSON> Woodfork </PERSON> said he did n't know how long it would last, although he heard it was to end Monday night. Leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION> have long been pressuring Mayor <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Barthelemy </PERSON> to enter the city's first collective bargaining agreement with the union. The union claims a membership of about 900 of the 1,100-member police force. <PERSON> Barthelemy </PERSON>, who was out of town Monday and unavailable for comment, has refused to recognize <ORGANIZATION> PANO </ORGANIZATION> as a collective bargaining group. Union President <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Cannatella </PERSON> did not return telephone calls and there was no word from the union on whether it had called for th