<FIRST>r w PM-EnergyEfficiency     07-12 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Energy Efficiency,520</SECOND>
<NOTE>For Release 10:30 a.m. EDT;
^Research Group Calls For Fuel, Gas-Guzzler Taxes</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should raise gasoline taxes by 50 cents a gallon, require cars to get 45 miles per gallon and boost the gas-guzzler tax to raise money for rebates to buyers of fuel-efficient cars, an organization of environmentalists, scientists and business executives said today. Those were central measures in a program outlined by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> for an Energy-Efficient Economy that would set a national goal of maintaining momentum in improving energy efficiency for the rest of the century. `` Energy efficiency does not require sacrifice,'' the group argued in its report. `` We do not advocate saving energy as an end in itself. It makes sense only when saving energy costs less than providing energy, including environmental damage and security risks in the comparison.'' Environmental risks of inefficiency are severe, the group said. Man-made gases, notably carbon dioxide produced by fossil fuels, threaten to warm the earth by as much as eight degrees Fahrenheit in the next century, raising sea levels and drastically changing patterns of rainfall and drought _ a process some scientists say is under way. Increasing the 9-cent-per-gallon federal gasoline tax by 10 cents annually for five years _ three years if crude oil prices double _ would yield $ 40 billion to $ 60 billion a year. Such a tax would help make sure `` consumers are given a price signal that better reflects the real cost of the resource and encourages conservation.'' Some money could be rebated to the poor through income tax provisions. Cars, now required to get 26 mpg, should get 45 mpg by 2000. `` It need not be so'' that the standards would mean less safety from lighter weight if cars are carefully designed, the group said. Cars twice as efficient as current models would cost $ 200 to $ 800 more, the group estimated. The increase would be recouped over the life of the car through lower cost of operation. A stiffer `` gas-guzzler'' tax, which can reach more than $ 2,000 now but generally applies to only a few luxury cars like <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION>, would discourage production of highly inefficient cars and provide funds _ more than $ 1.1 billion a year in 1994 _ to encourage purchase of `` gas sippers.'' The rebate could be `` on the order of $ 1,000'' for models with mileage 50 percent better than today's best _ implying rebates for cars getting about 75 mpg. Energy used per dollar of economic activity declined at a rate of about 2.7 percent per year from 1976 through 1986, and was still declining at a 2.5 percent per year during the economic recovery of 1983 through 1986. The 1986 oil price collapse discouraged further gains, and the decline was only 0.5 percent in 1987. The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says it expects gains of about 0.9 percent a year for the rest of the century. A reasonable international goal would be annual reductions of 2 percent, and `` We suggest that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> set an example by pursuing a goal of at least 2.5 percent per year'' until 2000, the group said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
