<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     07-12 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drought Expected To Have Limited Impact On Rice Crop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drought could have some impact on the nation's rice crop this year but not in the way heat and dry weather have shriveled corn and soybean prospects, according to <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> analysts The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rice harvest is all from irrigated land, says <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Childs </PERSON> of the Department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. But that does n't necessarily mean rice is drought proof. Much will depend on how the heat affects rice plants and on irrigation practices, including reduced yields from rising water costs, he said Monday. But generally, the drought is not expected to chew deeply into rice this year, at least `` not like you're seeing in the other commodities,'' <PERSON> Childs </PERSON> said. According to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> projections as of June 9, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rice harvest this year could be around 157 million hundredweight, up nearly a fourth from 127.7 million in 1987. Total rice use also is growing, says the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in its latest outlook report. And this growth is expected to continue in 1988-89. Overall, rice demand has increased by 20 million hundredweight in the last four years. `` Greater consumer preference for grain-based foods, aggressive marketing by rice industry organizations and processors, and wider availability of easy-to-prepare rice products have helped raise consumption,'' the report said. `` Growth in the <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> and Hispanic segment of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> population and increasing popularity of <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> and Oriental foods among all Americans have also helped expand consumption.'' Another growth has been in the amount of rice used to make beer _ an estimated 17 million hundredweight this year, up from less than 14 million in 1984-85. `` Brewers' use makes up about 20 percent of total domestic consumption and continues to show year-to-year increases,'' the report said. `` <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION>, the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> brewery, uses rice exclusively s an adjunct in several of its products. Gains in market share by this company over the past several years have helped increase rice use in beer, even though growth in total beer consumption has slowed.'' In all, domestic rice use may be about 83.5 million hundredweight in 1988-89, up from 80.8 million in 1987-88 and 76.3 million in 1986-87. Rice exports are forecast at 77 million hundredweight, up from 70 million last year but down from 85.4 million in 1986-87. `` Assuming normal weather in major rice exporting countries, -LRB- export -RRB- competition likely will be intense,'' the report said. Expectations of smaller rice supplies in 1987-88 triggered rice price increases, and in early 1988 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cash prices were substantially higher than world prices. However, those eased when major importers spurned the higher-priced <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rice. `` Also, expectations of increased exports from <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> further weakened world prices,'' the report added. `` Assuming normal weather, world production will increased in 1988-89 and keep prices below -LRB- the level of -RRB- 1987-88.'' For <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producers, rice prices may be in the range of $ 5 to $ 7 per hundredweight, down from $ 7 to $ 7.25 in 1987-88 but above the average of $ 3.75 in 1986-87, the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A recent survey by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurers </ORGANIZATION> shows that more than 370,000 farmers bought multiple-peril crop insurance this year, a 19 percent increase from 1987. `` Considering that most of these producers acted before there was evidence of a drought indicates that the crop insurance program is taking hold in the farm country as a risk-management tool,'' said <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Gantz </PERSON>, executive vice president of the association. The signup deadline in most areas was April 15, well before the severe drought conditions set in, he said. <PERSON> Gantz </PERSON> said preliminary estimates show 65 million to 70 million acres will likely be protected by crop insurance this year, compared with 62 million in 1987. The face value of protection of insurance written in 1987 was more than $ 6 billion and probably will increase this year, he said. `` These are producers who did n't want to wait for the federal government to come along with a handout,'' <PERSON> Gantz </PERSON> said in his report. `` They acted in a businesslike manner to protect their own farms and their own families from possible disaster.'' The multiple-peril crop insurance program began seven years ago and includes commercial companies that are reinsured against catastrophic losses by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION>, an agency of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FCIC </ORGANIZATION> also handles insurance directly through master marketers, who account for about 20 percent of the total. <PERSON> Gantz </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FCIC </ORGANIZATION> has indicated there will be no program changes in 1989 for most crops, beginning with those that will be planted this fall.
