<FIRST>r i PM-GorbachevExcerpts     07-12 0820</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev Excerpts,0851</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Remarks to Polish Parliament</HEAD>
<HEAD>With ^PM-Poland-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The following are excerpts, translated from Russian by the official Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, of Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s speech Monday to the Polish parliament, the Sejm, in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 On Soviet-Polish relations: There is still much in Soviet-Polish relations that does not meet the needs of both sides. ... This applies to direct human contacts as well. New crossings will be set up on the Soviet-Polish border, the possibilities of contacts across the border will be expanded and more railway and air lines will connect our countries. The idea of establishing a ferry between <LOCATION> Szscecin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> is being discussed. ... Our joint history is a rich, full-blooded history of two neighboring peoples. We have causes for pride, -LRB- but -RRB- there are things that have to be revealed and shown more fully. This history also has its complexities, what is called ` blank spots.' Notions that are based more on emotions rather than on strict scientific knowledge form at times around them. There is only one road to the truth here: study of facts, calm comparison of viewpoints and scientific discussions. History can not be replayed, but lessons can and should be drawn from it.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 On the <LOCATION> East-West </LOCATION> ideology battle: It is very important in these conditions to clear the ideological struggle of foul play. Psychological warfare and cultivation of mistrust among nations are incompatible with the norms of civilized state-to-state contacts. It is essential to do away with the preaching of militarism, hatred and enmity so that differences between countries become a stimulus for cooperation rather than a hindrance to it. The nations need the truth about one another. Western society has a poor knowledge of realities in the socialist world. It has been hammered into people's heads there since they were in diapers that the Communists are the bad guys who have enslaved their peoples and are sharpening their knives against the free nations of the West. ... We have to abandon our own simplistic approaches in presenting Western realities as well. It is imperative to see all the diversity, the complexity and equivocality, the contradictoriness of what is happening in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> countries _ in economic, political, social and other spheres.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 On conventional arms: As far as the governments of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> countries are concerned, they traditionally look at conventional arms as a legitimate component of power politics and uphold the nuclear deterence concept. While paying lip service to the need to reduce conventional arms, they continue in fact building up their military resources. ... We would, for instance, be prepared to withdraw our matching aircraft from forward-deployment sites in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> if <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> agrees not to base its 72 F-16 fighter-bombers, rejected by <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. ... The time has come for deeper troops and arms cuts in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and this requires expediting work in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> to hammer out a mandate for opening negotiations both on the reduction of conventional forces and armaments and on confidence-building measures on a Europe-wide scale. ... We suggest effecting the cuts in three phases: At the first phase, all the imbalances and asymmetries between <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> as regards both troop strength and primary arms are to be identified and eliminated. This approach could be applied both to the entire <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> continent as a whole and to its individual regions, for example <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, etc. For identifying the imbalances and asymmetries, we suggest exchanging initial data _ even before the talks or simultaneously with their commencement _ in amounts to be dictated by the agreed subject of the negotiations Careful checks on the data, including on-site inspections, are to be run soon after the start of the talks so as to avoid a repetition of the sad experience of the debates on numbers that once deadlocked the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> talks on central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Let me note in passing that if <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> shows readiness, we can discuss the issue of the imbalances and asymmetries even before the start of the formal talks, in connection with the exchanges of data on troops and weaponry. At the second phase, the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Treaty forces are to be reduced by 500,000 men on each side from the levels existing after the elimination of the imbalances and asymmetries. The cuts are to be carried out by disbanding military units along with elimination of their organic arms. At the third phase, the cuts are to be continued so as to finally lend the military units of both military alliances a purely defensive nature. All the reduction phases would provide for effective verificaiton arrangements, including on-site inspections. I would like to add to this that we are prepared not only at the third phase but also from the very start of the cuts to come to terms on the priority reduction of tactical nuclear weapons, tactical strike aircraft and tanks.
</TEXT>
