<HEAD>Convention Closes Without Resolving Homosexual Ordination Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM IRWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> leaders have closed their 69th General Convention without adopting a proposal that could have encouraged the ordination of homosexuals. A resolution Monday expanding `` access to the selection process for ordination'' for all persons, including homosexuals _ but refusing to recognize a right to ordination for all _ fell one vote short of passage in the church's House of Deputies. The 900-member House of Deputies, divided between lay and clerical church members, and the 200-member House of Bishops establish policy for the 2.7 million-member church, whose 10-day convention ended Monday. The conventions are held every three years. Delegates considered almost 500 resolutions at the convention, which opened July 2. But the question of ordaining gay priests dominated the final days of the convention. Current church law says candidates for ordination must be at least 21 years of age and pass prescribed medical, psychological and academic tests. But leaders of some of the church's 118 dioceses in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have ordained homosexual priests without running afoul of Episcopal canon law. In 1979, the 66th General Convention approved a resolution stating in part, `` We believe it is not appropriate for this church to ordain a practicing homosexual.'' That resolution, however, is not a part of canon law, which draws a distinction between homosexual activity, which it says is sinful, and homosexual orientation, which it says is not. Church leaders on both sides of the homosexual debate agreed that Monday's vote left the issue unresolved. <ORGANIZATION> Canon </ORGANIZATION> law was left intact and thus maintained discretion within the dioceses as to consideration of homosexual candidates for the priesthood, said the Rt. Rev. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, bishop of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` I'm not unhappy that it did n't pass,'' said the Rt. Rev. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, bishop of <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. `` We are not of one mind on the subject. Until we are, we should be cautious of passing anything until we can speak with authority.'' `` I was disappointed that, to the portion of people who tend to see themselves as being disenfranchised from the church, -LRB- approval of the resolution -RRB- would have given some pastoral concern,'' said the Rt. Rev. <PERSON> O'Kelley </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON>, bishop of central <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. But, <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON> added: `` It does n't cripple the church. Homosexuals are involved in the ordination process in many dioceses already. It is happening anyway.'' Confusion over parliamentary procedure marred the homosexual debate, church leaders said. `` I've been a bishop a long time ... and I have never heard as many parliamentary procedure tactics as I have seen in this house this week,'' Presiding Bishop <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION>. Also Monday, both houses approved a resolution opposing `` abortion as a means of birth control, family planning or sex selection.'' The resolution in its final form acknowledged that women in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have a legal right to medically safe abortion. But it also deleted a passage expressing the church's opposition to any government action barring a woman's right to abortion. Delegates on Monday also approved a resolution extending for two years the experimental use oelief and practice, curtail masculine references to God as much as possible. The church's <ORGANIZATION> Liturgical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> later will evaluate the experiment. Among the final resolutions approved was one calling frrowly rejected the resolution Sunday, when some delegates claimed the boycott would hurt <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses. But the deputies reversed their vote Monday to express solidarity with Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, who has promoted the boycott as a means of protesting racial segregation in that nation.
