<HEAD>Black Boxes Could Clear Up Questions About Airliner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The `` black box'' recorders from the downed Iranian jetliner in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> should be recoverable, clearing up questions about the plane's flight path and whether its pilots received radio warnings, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aviation experts say. Several <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aviation experts, speaking Monday on condition that they not be identified by name, speculated that the recorders likely survived the crash unless the missile from the <LOCATION> USS </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> hit directly where they were located in the rear of the aircraft. And although the commander of the Iranian <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> denied the recorders had been found, a published report from <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> quoted unidentified salvage experts as saying that the so-called `` black boxes'' had been recovered from the gulf waters. All commercial jetliners are required to have the recorders, one that monitors cockpit conversation and another that tracks operations of the plane. They are housed in separate boxes that actually are painted orange, but often become blackened by fire in airline crashes. They are located in the tail section of the plane and designed to withstand severe impacts. The <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> A-300 shot down by the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> on July 3, killing all 290 people aboard, was believed to have been equipped with a sophisticated digital flight recorder that would provide a broad range of operating information as well as a cockpit voice recorder. If they are found in good condition and were properly maintained by the Iranians, the recorders could provide a wealth of information to investigators including a detailed reproduction of the plane's flight path from the time of takeoff, the experts said. The cockpit voice recorder, which monitors radio communications and cockpit conversation on a continuous 30-minute loop, would indicate whether the <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> pilots received repeated radio warnings as maintained by the Pentagon. The cockpit tape would be expected to cover the entire flight of the Iranian jetliner as well as the period during which the plane was taxiing and awaiting takeoff at <PERSON> Bandar </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> for the short trip across the gulf to <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION>. In addition to radio communications, the cockpit tape would reveal conversation within the cockpit and indicate whether the pilots might have intended anything other than a routine flight and whether they might have been distracted by mechanical or other problems causing them to fly off course or fail to acknowledge radio warnings, the experts suggested. The flight data recorder in the A-300 is a sophisticated digital version that provides more than 80 measures involving the plane's flight operations including altitude, heading, air speed and whether the plane was experiencing any flight difficulties The Pentagon has said that the commercial jetliner was perceived in part as a threat to the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> because of the plane's unusual flight path and speed. Officials said the jetliner was descending, traveling faster than normal for a commercial airliner, and heading directly toward the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ship. There also have been discrepancies as to how far the A-300 was off from its intended flight path.
