<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Part of a deposition by Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> gives conflicting indications of whether he knew about planned payments to the Israeli <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1985. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocap </PERSON> on Monday released a 12-page portion of the deposition given to the office of independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>. The deposition was the focus of news reports over the weekend that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> gave differing recollections between November 1987 and February about planned payments to the Israeli party. The planned payments could have constituted a violation of the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act. In the deposition, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was asked by <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>'s office whether he understood that the Israeli government and the labor party were to receive funds from the pipeline. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, referring to a 1985 memo he received from longtime friend <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> about the planned labor party payments, said: `` I ca n't recall specifically, but that certainly would be consistent with my understanding and would explain why Mr. -LRB- then-Israeli Prime Minister and labor party chief <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> was personally interested.'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was then asked whether he had any specific recollection of <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> telling him of the labor party's interest or financial stake in the operation. `` I have a general recollection but even as we sit here now I do n't know how that was all going to be achieved,'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> replied. Pressed to elaborate, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said, `` I have a general recollection that the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> was very much interested.'' He added that he could n't recall except through the words of <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s memo in front of him, which `` is consistent with my recollection. Then, for the ensuing 10 pages of the deposition, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> says that <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> did n't make any reference to the labor party's stake in the pipeline in a conversation the two men had, that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> never discussed with <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> where the pipeline money would go and that he never discussed with <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> the propriety of the labor party receiving any funds. Later in the deposition, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> also said that as to an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> stake and labor party stake in the project, `` I have no even general recollection of the benefit to the labor party other than as is expressed in that ... memorandum that you showed me.'' Finally, after 12 pages of questioning about the planned labor party payments, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> suggested he had n't focused on the portion of the memo from <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> relating to planned payments to the labor party until he was questioned that day. After news media reports surfaced early this year about the <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> memo's reference to planned labor party payments, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said publicly that he did n't recall reading that portion of <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s memo relating to any such plan. The lawyer, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocap </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> filed a declaration with <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>'s office after reporters suggested that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s public statement did n't square with his earlier deposition. <PERSON> Rocap </PERSON> said information about the deposition apparently had been leaked to reporters. `` I was not stating that I had a recollection, specific or general, that the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> had a financial stake in the project,'' the Feb. 18. 1988, declaration said. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, which on Saturday published portions of independent counsel <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>'s 830-page report on the <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> investigation, said <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> concluded that the memo was the only `` direct evidence'' of a bribery plan and therefore insufficient to conclude that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> violated the law.
