<HEAD>Katyn One Word Not Uttered by Soviet Leader on Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Poland-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, speaking of painful episodes in their countries' shared history, say no one should shirk from examining the past honestly. But the Soviet and Polish Communist leaders stopped short Monday of uttering the one word that symbolizes the most painful episode in Polish-Soviet relations and the one historical `` blank spot'' most Poles want explicated. Neither said `` <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>,'' the name of the forest in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> where the bodies of about 4,300 Polish army officers were uncovered by Nazi troops during World War II. Each of the officers, representing the cream of Polish society, was bound and shot with a single bullet to the base of the skull. Official Soviet and Polish histories have long maintained that the officers were killed by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> in 1941, but independent historians and most Poles believe they were killed in 1940 on the orders of <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> by the <ORGANIZATION> NKVD </ORGANIZATION> secret police, predecessor of the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION>. A joint Soviet-Polish historical commission was charged last year with investigating the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> massacre and other painful `` blank spots,'' including the 1920 war between <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s murder of virtually all leading members of the <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in the late 1930s. But Polish officials have in recent days been playing down the possibility of any dramatic admission by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> during his trip to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> this week. On Monday, when <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> began the six-day visit to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s largest <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc ally, a small group of young men climbed atop a bus stop in central <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> and unfurled a banner reading, `` We demand the truth about <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>. Reparation for deportations.'' `` <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> is a symbol of cruelty,'' said leaflets they handed out. `` It is a still-bleeding blank spot, the explanation of which all Poles demand.'' Among the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> victims and 11,000 other officers interned by the Soviets whose fates remain unknown, there were 800 doctors, 50 professors and hundreds of engineers, lawyers, teachers and writers, the leaflets said. `` Poles have the right to know the truth about this holocaust on their outstanding fellow countrymen,'' the leaflets said. In his speech to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s parliament on Monday, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> promised that more would be said about `` blank spots.'' `` There are things that have to be revealed and shown more fully,'' he said. `` There is only one road to the truth here: study of facts, calm comparison of viewpoints and scientific discussions. History can not be replayed, but lessons can and should be drawn from it.'' <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> voiced a similar theme: `` Every crime and every human suffering have a moral dimension. They can not be crossed out and one must not remain silent about them. `` Joint works of Polish and Soviet historians are under way. We hope that they will allow us to better learn about the background, course and nature of various dramatic events.'' Anticipating reporters' questions about <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>, officials scheduled a press conference after the parliament session by the Polish and Soviet chairmen of the historical commission investigating <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>. The chairmen said they had some reason to question to the Soviet source materials on <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>, but could not say anything more without extensive further study.
