 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials said they do n't expect damage to a test booster will delay the tentatively scheduled September launch of the first space shuttle since the 1986 Challenger disaster. The accident will, however, postpone the final test-firing of <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>'s redesigned booster from July 25 until the end of August, officials said. The booster was damaged Saturday when a worker testing one of the motor's three field joints inadvertently switched pressurization lines and damaged insulation that helps contain superheated gasses during flight, <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Rocky </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said Monday. However, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Campion </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` We do not expect it to affect the STS-26 launch schedule.'' STS-26 is the designation for the first flight of a space shuttle since the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion destroyed Challenger and killed seven crew members. An 11-member panel from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> will meet next week to evaluate the mishap. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> said the test motor will have to be partially disassembled for evaluation and possible repairs. `` After the rocket is opened up at the joint, we'll have something more to say,'' said <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Atchison </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` At this point, our best estimate is that we do n't anticipate a delay. The damaged test rocket already contained severe intentional flaws designed to determine whether the redesigned joints can withstand the heat and pressure of launch even in the event of some failures. The test rocket incorporates a new design created after Challenger exploded after its launch from the Kennedy Space Center. The explosion was blamed on a faulty booster joint that allowed a plume of superhot gas to burn through an O-ring, triggering the blast.
