<HEAD>Talks On Cutting Long-Range Nuclear Stocks Resume</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS two grafs for grafs 6-7 pvs, ``Kampelman and ...'' to
UPDATE with opening session over; pickup 8th graf pvs, ``Kampelman,
chief ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Superpower talks on reducing long-range nuclear arsenals resumed today after a seven-week break with both sides identifying at least two major hurdles toward completing a draft treaty. Before the opening session, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> chief delegate <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Kampelman </PERSON> reaffirmed <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s stand that a pact that would halve each side's stockpile `` should not be held hostage'' to limits sought by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plans for a large-scale space defense against ballistic missiles. The other chief source of disagreement centers on Soviet insistence on limiting sea-launched cruise missiles. Asked whether negotiators see a possible fifth superpower summit or the end of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s presidency in January as a deadline, <PERSON> Kampelman </PERSON> told reporters talks will `` continue no matter who is president and no matter who the leader of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is. `` I do n't think important issues should be governed by the calendar,'' he said. `` If it takes longer, fine. If it takes shorter, fine.'' <PERSON> Kampelman </PERSON>, chief Soviet negotiator <PERSON> Alexei </PERSON> <PERSON> Obukhov </PERSON> and their full delegations met for about two hours at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mission to launch the 10th round of <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> talks since March 1985. The session then recessed for the day, and no date was immediately announced for the next session. The ninth round of talks recessed before the May 29-June 2 summit between <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, which produced only slight progress toward a long-range nuclear forces treaty. The superpower leaders then ordered negotiators to continue `` energetically and purposefully.'' No end date has been announced for this new round. The chief negotiators hinted that a breakthrough is not in sight. `` Do n't look for drama,'' <PERSON> Kampelman </PERSON> told reporters Monday. `` We're at a stage now where hard work is required rather than drama.'' <PERSON> Obukhov </PERSON> warned after his arrival Sunday: `` We do not want to lose momentum.'' While both negotiators said the talks have come `` a long way,'' <PERSON> Kampelman </PERSON> also noted, `` Much that is important still remains to be solved.'' He said a draft could still be completed under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and voiced hope the new round will, `` at the very least, significantly narrow the differences between us.'' Both sides agree that the proposed Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty should cut each side's stocks over seven years to an overall limit of 6,000 nuclear warheads and 1,600 launchers, such as heavy bombers and land-based intercontinental missiles. Some details of monitoring compliance with a future pact are also settled, but both negotiators stressed more work was needed. <PERSON> Obukhov </PERSON> told reporters progress `` now depends primarily'' on resolving disputes over <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plans to develop a space-based missile defense system, called the Strategic Defense Initiative, and on limiting the deployment of long-range sea-launched cruise missiles. `` We reject the Soviet attempts to use these negotiations to have us end our Strategic Defense Initiative,'' <PERSON> Kampelman </PERSON> said. For sea-launched cruise missiles, the Soviets have proposed limits and called for anti-cheating measures including inspections of warships. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has balked, saying the weapons can not be reliably detected. On Monday, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiator <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanmer </PERSON> called the Soviet verification proposals `` totally impractical'' and said current prospects for resolving the issue are dim. Last December, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> signed a treaty scrapping all intermediate-range nuclear forces. Both countries ratified that pact shortly before the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit.
