<HEAD>`Domino' Transplant Donor Dies 14 Months After Procedure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A cystic fibrosis victim who became the nation's first living heart donor has died of respiratory failure, 14 months after receiving a heart and lungs transplant at <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hopkins </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON>, 29, who donated his heart to another man after he received a heart-lung transplant, died while awaiting a second transplant, his cardiologist, Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Traill </PERSON>, said Monday. House's respiratory failure
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 his rejection of the transplanted lungs, the cardiologist said. Meanwhile, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Couch </PERSON>, 39, of <PERSON> Yardley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, who received <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s original heart, continues to do well, <PERSON> Traill </PERSON> said Couch had suffered from congestive heart failure. House received the heart and lungs of a brain-dead accident victim in a 17-hour operation on May 10-11, 1987. He needed a lung transplant, but doctors did a heart-lung transplant because the procedure is safer. House donated his healthy heart to Couch in the nation's first so-called domino donor transplant, hospital spokesman <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Kibak </PERSON> said. House `` had a good summer last year, a good fall,'' said <PERSON> Traill </PERSON>. `` But from about that onwards, he began to do progessively less well because of the system rejection.'' House had been waiting since February for a second double transplant, <PERSON> Traill </PERSON> said. Couch `` was sad and distressed,'' by <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s death, said <PERSON> Traill </PERSON>. `` It did n't come as a complete surprise to -LRB- Couch -RRB-, because he knew Mr. <PERSON> House </PERSON> had been doing poorly. They had been keeping in touch.'' Cystic fibrosis causes production of a thick, sticky mucus that clogs the lungs and digestive system. It is the nation's most common inherited disease, afflicting about 30,000 Americans, and usually kills victims by the time they reach their mid-20s.
