<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: To update with Bentsen selection as Dukakis running mate,
insert new 6th graf, bgng: Dukakis today; sub 20th graf bgng: And
it is; sub next to last graf, bgng: He declared; adds editor's note
at end
   </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is n't making life easy for <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his aides undoubtedly hoped next week's Democratic National Convention would allow the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor to bask _ solo _ in the warmth of a prime-time party unity festival, the next step toward a showdown with <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the fall. That was until <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> decided to campar the vice presidential nomination, to arrange a grand arrival in this convention city and encourage a few thousand of his closest friends to join him and deign arduously foride the proposed bare-bones platform crafted by the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> forces. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was asked a few days ago whether he was worried about stealing some of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' thunder. `` It has nothing to do with thunder,'' was his taunting reply. `` Mr. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had no intention of bringing any thunder to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> today stole some of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s thunder. According a well-placed <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> source, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> will announce later today that he has selected Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> BWe intend to have an effective, informative convention that would inspire our nation, unify our party and take us to victory,'' he said Monday. But he also said that his actions in the future will be influenced by the treatment his candidacy and platform proposals receive. `` The conclusion of those steps will in some measure determine what our fall activities will be,'' he said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has an uncanny ability to remain on the stage long after other politicians would have departed. He remained a campaigner in the primary season long after a conventional politician would have run out of money and called it quits. He campaigned assiduously for the vice presidential nomination, while others who want it as much or more practically blush anytime the subject is mentioned within their earshot. Who else in American politics would announce one day that he had decided whether he would accept an offer to join <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on the ticket, but would n't tell anyone what his decision was And who else would describe as `` unknown quantities'' all the other contenders for the vice presidential nomination? His platform issues will be debated on national television next week if it goes that far. He will speak during prime time on the second night of the convention. His name will be entered into nomination for president the following night. And it is conceivable that his name could be put into nomination for vice president on the final night in a final, symbolic clash with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. That, of course, would give him the chance to go to the podium once more, perhaps to bestow his blessing at last on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his running mate. But even now, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is making sure the spotlight does n't turn away from him when the convention ends. He declared on Monday _ before the choice of <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> became known _ that if <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> offered him second place on the ticket `` I would accept it.'' He said he assured <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' emissary <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> that he would be a loyal vice president. But <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said that if he were not chosen, he would expect further discussions with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> before defining what role he will play in the fall campaign.
</TEXT>
