<HEAD>Last Playboy Club In U.S. Is Closing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The last <ORGANIZATION> Playboy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ the 5-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Lansing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Playboy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Hilton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inn </LOCATION> here _ will close at the end of the month, the hotel's sales director said. Playboy Clubs in <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> closed at the end of April. The first <ORGANIZATION> Playboy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> was opened in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> in 1960 by <ORGANIZATION> Playboy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> publisher <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Hefner </PERSON>, according to <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziffra </PERSON>, licensing manager of Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Playboy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. In the early 1970s, she said, there were as many as 22 Playboy Clubs around the country. The decision to close the Lansing club coincided with the Hilton Hotel's effort to create a new image, said <PERSON> Shelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahlers </PERSON>, the hotel's sales director. For most of its life, the <ORGANIZATION> Playboy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> was a $ 25-a-year club geared to males, said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Brook </PERSON>, the hotel's food and beverage manager. In May of 1987, because of a decline in business, it was opened to the general public. `` It's the end of an era,'' <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> said. `` It was a glorious club.''
