<TEXT>
 Reporters, artists, photographers and columnists for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> withheld their bylines from today's editions of the newspaper to protest the two years they have gone without a labor contract with the company. The last contract between Post management and the <ORGANIZATION> Washington-Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> expired July 9, 1986. In a flier distributed in the newsroom, <PERSON> Lew </PERSON> <PERSON> Diuguid </PERSON>, head of the bargaining committee of the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> unit of the union, accused the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> of `` failure to bargain in good faith.'' The guild said it planned a two-day byline strike. Union leaders say there is a two-tier pay system which established a lower minimum scale for those hired after 1976, causing what they say is pay discrimination by race and sex. The union also opposes what it says is a `` pattern of force-outs of ` expensive' senior employees.'' In a statement, Executive Editor <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradlee </PERSON> and Managing Editor <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Downie </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said, `` We all want a new contract between the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> and the guild'' and that the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> `` has now signed contracts with every one of the other 10 unions'' represented at the newspaper. The statement denied existence of a two-tier wage system and said the Post is not trying to force out higher paid employees. The last negotiated contract between the Guild and the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> established a top minimum pay rate of $ 664.35 a week. <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Polaski </PERSON>, administrator for the guild, said that under company-imposed rules pay has been raised, leaving an av