<HEAD>Thornburgh's Law Enforcement Roots Date Back to 1969</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Meese-Successor Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 2 grafs new to update with announcement; picks up 3rd
graf pvs, Former members.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s selection of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> as his next attorney general marks a return for the tough-minded former <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> governor to the law enforcement roots that first propelled him into the public eye in 1969. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said today that he had chosen <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> to replace <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, who announced last week that he would resign by early August. Former members of <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s gubernatorial administration were quick to point out his reputation for integrity and that he eliminated the corruption that tainted the tenure of his predecessor, Democrat <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapp </PERSON>. They also noted the close ties <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> has kept with the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. As governor, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, 55, frequently testified on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> on behalf of the president's proposal for line-item veto power and a constitutional amendment to balance the budget. He has turned down offers to head the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, and was considered for the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> post in 1985. As governor, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said his budget proposals held spending increases to less than the rate of inflation for eight straight years. He championed a controversial welfare reform law that limited cash benefits to three months a year for an estimated 68,000 people considered `` able-bodied.'' But it was