 Two unarmed Minuteman 3 intercontinental ballistic missiles were successfully launched today, the 133rd and 134th in a series of tests of the weapons system, officials said. The first missile was fired at 4:40 a.m. from an EC-135 jet, the military equivalent of the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 707, said Capt. <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Waddell </PERSON> of the base information office. The missile reached its target in the <LOCATION> Kwajalien </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atoll </LOCATION> test range, 4,200 miles southwest of the base in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Waddell </PERSON> said. The second missile was launched at 6:21 a.m. from the ground at the base, 150 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The second missile followed the same path as the first and reached the target range about 30 minutes after launch, said Airman 1st Class <PERSON> Ann-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Townsend </PERSON>. Both missiles were launched by a task force from F.E. <ORGANIZATION> Warren </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>.
