<HEAD>Officials Meet For Last Day of Talks on Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 South African, Angolan, <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials met today for the last day of their talks on ending South African rule in neighboring <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> and withdrawing <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The military and political officials held the talks at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> base on Governors Island in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> harbor. The participants in the talks have released no comments on the outcome of the talks. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has said it would accept a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolution calling for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s independence under black majority rule only after the withdrawal of an estimated 50,000 Cuban troops backing <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s Marxist government. Anti-communist rebels, backed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, have been fighting government troops since 1985. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, have said the timetable for the Cuban pullout has not been set and is the most difficult issue in the talks. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goal is a complete Cuban withdrawal within one year, when a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> resolution has proposed granting independence to <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, also called <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> have said that the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> withdrawal should take place over four years. <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> has been convulsed by civil war since it gained independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1975. The government, supported by <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, has been fighting anti-communist rebels belonging to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has repeatedly sent troops across the border from <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> into <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> to support the rebel forces. The Angolan government is seeking the permanent withdrawal of all South African forces from its territory. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has increased its troop strength in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> from 35,000 to 37,000 soldiers last fall to about 50,000 now, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have said. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has had administrative control over <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> since 1920. The four parties involved in the current talks first met for talks in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in May and again last month in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
