<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, apparently having chosen <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> as his vice presidential running mate, smiled and joked with news photographers today but declined to talk about the choice that sources said he'd made. The sources, who commented only on condition they not be named, said the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> senator was chosen late Monday night in a meeting among <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, his long-time confidant <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> and campaign manager <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Estrich </PERSON>. The word was passed to <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> late in the night or early this morning and he accepted. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, 67, was flying to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> today to meet with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> refused to speak to reporters when he arrived at the Statehouse today, although he allowed photographers into his office as he sifted through paperwork. `` It's kind of fun, this business running for the presidency,'' he said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> met Monday night a few hours after <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> talked with <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. As <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> left the house, he was asked if the selection process was over and he replied, `` He -LRB- <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> -RRB- can always ask more questions if he wants.'' Asked if a decision had been made, the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> lawyer said, `` No comment.'' While he waited for <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> appeared in his yard shortly after dark, dressed in shorts and a short-sleeve shirt and mowed his lawn with a push mower. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was meeting today with party chairman from around the country, a session designed to assure them that they would be included in planning for the fall campaign. `` We asked for the meeting,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruvolo </PERSON>. `` We wanted to get things squared away.'' <PERSON> Ruvolo </PERSON> said he had no idea what the status was of his state's vice-presidential favorite, Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> Speculation about the potential vice presidential choice was a top subject of conversation in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> among the early arrivals for the convention. The top contenders were believed to include <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. Also on the short list were Sens. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and Reps. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. The contenders themselves were maintaining a discreet silence _ except for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> who said for the first time that `` if it was offered to me I would accept it.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> made his statement after meeting with <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, his first public declaration that he would accept the spot if <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> offered it. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said he gave <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> the detailed personal financial information that has been solicited from prospective running mates, and said he offered his `` candid view as to the office of vice president ... and what I thought my qualifications would be.'' <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> refused to discuss the substance of the discussion, saying only that it was `` an excellent meeting ... very productive.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said `` it is self-evident'' that he wants to be vice president and said he assured <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> that he would be a loyal second to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. If he is not on the ticket, said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, he would expect further discussions with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> about his role in the fall campaign.
