<HEAD>Crude Falls to Lowest Close Since Late '86, Outlook Lower Still</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 4 grafs new with prices falling further today, picks up
5th graf pvs, Refined products...; Version moved on financial
circuits</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crude oil prices dropped sharply for the second straight day today, tumbling toward the $ 14-a-barrel level in reaction to fears of a relentless supply glut and <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s failure to restrain output. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, a sensitive barometer of price trends, the August-delivery price for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> was $ 14.49 a barrel by midday, down 29 cents from the 20-month closing low of $ 14.78 set Monday. `` The market is awash in crude and the focus has returned to that,'' said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON>, an energy futures trader with the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` The market just looks extremely bearish.'' The decline Monday erased gains made last week, which were based on fears of supply disruptions caused by a major oil platform explosion in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. Refined products traded on the exchange also fell sharply, although not as steeply as crude. Wholesale heating oil for August delivery fell 2.06 cents a gallon to 41.33 cents, while wholesale unleaded gasoline fell 1.04 cents a gallon to 52.13 cents. At one point during the day, crude prices rose briefly on a news report that the price-monitoring committee of the 13-member Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries might confer soon. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s official news agency said the meeting might be held after the cartel's general secretary, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON>, met with officials of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> for talks `` concerning the current oil market situation.'' Output cheating by members of the cartel has weakened the market seriously recently, making <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 18-per-barrel target price more remote than ever The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> has been mentioned as a significant violator. Said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, a trader at <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s energy futures unit, `` Crude has gotten down to a supply-demand scenario. There's simply too much. I think the market needs to see something of substance. The rhetoric of <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> is ridiculous. Every trader considers it ridiculous.'' By some analyst reckonings, the cartel now is pumping as much as 18.8 million barrels a day, more than 3 million barrels a day over its official ceiling of 15.06 million barrels.
