<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, wooing votes at the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> convention, promised today to have a `` positive civil rights agenda'' and paid tribute to <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> `` for running the race, for being heard.'' In an appearance before several thousand people at the 79th convention of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colored </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not mention reports of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' plans to name <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> as his running mate on the Democratic ticket <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, delivering his speech beneath a banner proclaiming, `` Vote, Be Heard,'' got a warm reception from the audience. He said he wanted to be heard `` because I do not intend to concede the vote of any American.'' The vice president, certain to be the Republican presidential nominee, said a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration would mark `` a new day'' from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. `` I will have a positive civil rights agenda,'' he pledged. `` I guarantee you I will be personally involved in protecting the civil rights of all Americans,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` This effort will be at the top of the agenda of my attorney general, and he or she will be directly accountable to me for results.'' The audience applauded loudly. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also said he had known <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, the runner-up in the Democratic primaries, for a long time in a friendly, personal way. `` And I do n't have to cover up the differences _ I have profound differences with <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> on many of these issues, but I salute him for running the race, for being heard, and he deserves a salute from us,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, again drawing loud applause from the audience. The vice president readily acknowledged that Republicans since the days of President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> have not been able to win much of the black vote. However, he pledged that if elected president his decisions `` will not depend on getting a certain percentage of the black vote. I want to do what is fair. I want to do what is right. And I want to do what is principled.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> promised that regardless of the black vote he gets `` you will be heard, I promise you that. You are going to be called on. You are going to be partners in my presidency.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is to address the convention tonight and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is to speak before it on Wednesday. While the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has been criticized as being insensitive to blacks, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has a good relationship with some black leaders and has promised that a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration would have a positive civil rights agenda. By a significant margin, blacks voted for <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mondale </ORGANIZATION> in 1984 and <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> in 1980 rather than the Reagan-Bush ticket. However, in opening the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> convention, <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooks </PERSON>, the group's executive director, said it would be a `` fatal mistake'' for Democrats to assume they have the black vote wrapped up. The <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> is the third special interest group that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has courted this week, following an appearance Sunday before Lithuanians and before a group of farm writers, editors and broadcasters on Monday. Responding to a question from the audience at the <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communicators </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he might consider Senate Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> or any of the other contenders in the Republican primary race as a running mate. The vice president said <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> was `` deservedly popular in agricultural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. He knows a great deal about it.'' `` But I just do n't want to start going through long lists or short lists -LRB- of candidates -RRB- because believe me, at this juncture, we do n't have them,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` I will say this about <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>. He and I went head on head,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> added. `` So did <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Haig </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>. ... `` My party has never been more unified going into a Republican convention than we are right now thanks to the way <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> and the others have been conducting themselves and their sense of advocacy,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` So the fact you ran against somebody certainly in my view would not preclude consideration of that person.'' Outlining factors that will influence his decision, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the fundamental criteria will be who _ man or woman _ is best qualified to take over if something happens to the president. `` I would want a certain philosophical compatability to be there,'' he said. `` Then I will do what all politicians do _ throw a little bit of seasoning in there for geography.'' However, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that factor was not important as it has been. `` I'll look who the Democrats pick and then we will have procedures for selecting, and they will be, getting, soliciting opinion from the senators, the Republicans and members of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committeee </ORGANIZATION> and congressmen and governors and all of that. `` And that will probably be done by the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` Sometimes that's been done in the past. `` And then I will make a very personal decision,'' he added. In a speech that he billed as non-partisan, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> nevertheless took several jabs at <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, saying, `` I am not the one who feels that the problems of agricultural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> can be solved by planting more belgian endive.'' He also said a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration would help farmers export more crops, `` not force farmers to produce less. That is the major difference.''
