<HEAD>Begin's Son Running for Parliament</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> `` Benny'' Begin brings the looks and mannerisms of his father, former Prime Minister <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> Begin </PERSON>, to his run for parliament and the nostalgia factor could be important for both him and his party. <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> <PERSON> Begin </PERSON>, a 45-year-old government geologist, is the first son of an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> prime minister to run for office. He was chosen this month as a candidate of the <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc, the right-wing alliance his father founded, in the Nov. 1 elections. He is taller and leaner but the hand and facial gestures, some of his rhetorical flourishes and even his tone of voice are almost identical to his father's. Party officials believe the Begin name on <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>'s list could help it win what promises to be a close contest with the center-left <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> for control of the <ORGANIZATION> Knesset </ORGANIZATION>, the 120-seat parliament. In an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> <PERSON> Begin </PERSON> insisted he can not fill his father's shoes. `` It is unreasonable to hang hopes on me because my name is Begin,'' he said. `` People like him are born very rarely.'' Begin said he sees little chance for territorial compromise or a peace agreement with neighboring <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, so believes like his father that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> should keep control of the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. `` I am not a prophet of doom,'' he said with a smile. `` I look at all the alternatives and seek the lesser evil, the one that does n't endanger <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s survival, which means maintaining absolute Israeli control over the land of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> west of the <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> Begin </PERSON>, 74, was born in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. His mix of charm and fiery rhetoric proved a winning formula for ending three decades of <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> government in 1977. In 1978 he shared the Nobel Peace Prize with the late Egyptian President <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> for the process leading to their peace treaty the next year, then resigned suddenly in 1983 and has been a recluse since. Associates and friends said <PERSON> Begin </PERSON> resigned because he was depressed about <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s loss of more than 650 soldiers in the invasion of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, which began under his leadership in 1982. <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> <PERSON> Begin </PERSON> refuses to speak about his father except to say, `` He's feeling fine, thank you'' and acknowledge the former prime minister as the source of his political aspirations. When interviewed during a party meeting at a country club in <LOCATION> Herzliya </LOCATION>, a seaside town, the younger Begin focused on his own political views. He delivered them with the same rhetorical style and sense of Jewish history as his father, pausing occasionally to sip grapefruit juice from a can or shake hands with well-wishers. He condemned the 7-month-old Palestinian rebellion in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>, which <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has occupied since capturing them from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in the 1967 war. `` The Arabs call it the ` intefadeh,' or uprising, but they are simply riots,'' he said. `` That's what they should be called. It is clear that this is a new method to carry out an old goal of the Arab nation to expel the Jews from the land of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> <PERSON> Begin </PERSON> characterized tough army measures used to quell <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> unrest as `` reasonable force'' and disputed the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s contention that a political process would resolve the conflict `` There is no political solution,'' he said, and a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state in the occupied territories `` would be another terrorist state between <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> which would try to take over all of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' `` As long as the Arab nation does n't relinquish its plan to destroy the land of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, there will unfortunately be no peaceful solution,'' Begin declared. The son was born in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and, unlike his father, rarely invokes the Nazi Holocaust as a rationale for his political views. He also is more soft-spoken. He has a doctorate in geology from <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and for the past decade has been studying the viability of building a nuclear power plant in the <LOCATION> Negev </LOCATION> desert. Begin said his role was to determine the risk of an earthquake in the area that could cause a nuclear disaster. <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> <PERSON> Begin </PERSON> has four daughters and two sons aged eight to 23. His wife, <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON>, 45, is a social worker for the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> who deals with people wounded in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s wars.
