<HEAD>White Activists To Participate In Municipal Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A white anti-apartheid coalition said Tuesday it would not adopt the election boycott strategy of black activists and instead would try to elect pro-integration candidates in municipal elections. The Five Freedoms Forum, which represents 25 human rights and religious groups, said the focus of its campaign would be to elect an anti-apartheid municipal council in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, the country's largest city Segregated elections for councils in white, black, mixed-race and Asian communities are scheduled nationwide for Oct. 26, the first time voters of all races will go to the polls on the same day. The government has outlawed public calls for an election boycott, but black activists have said they oppose participation in any elections until <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 26 million blacks are given voting rights on the national level. Prominent anti-apartheid clergymen two weeks ago defied the government ban and urged <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africans </LOCATION> not to vote in October. The Five Freedoms Forum, in a statement, said it was not criticizing those who favored a boycott of the elections. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Johannesburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, as a whites-only body, is a structure infected with the racism implicit in the government's apartheid policy,'' the statement said `` However, despite the inadequacy of these structures, we do not believe that any purpose would be served by calling on whites to boycott.'' The statement said the elections could be used as a vehicle for campaigning against apartheid laws such as the Group Areas Act, which establishes racially segregated residential districts. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a segregated society in which the blacks have no vote in national affairs, controlled by the 5 million whites. The government is spending more than $ 2 million on an advertising campaign to promote participation in the elections. Officials of <ORGANIZATION> Transvaal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION>, which includes <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, on Tuesday called on employers to help their black workers register to vote by obtaining forms that could be filled out at workplaces.
