<TEXT>
 A bus packed with hikers plunged off a mountain highway Tuesday in northern <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, killing at least 14 passengers and injuring 34, police said. The bus tumbled 200 feet down a deep valley from a steep road in <LOCATION> Balin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taoyuan </LOCATION>, 30 miles south of <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION>, police said. Taoyuan police reported 14 people died, but the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> put the death toll at 17. The police, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said about 10 of the injured people were seriously hurt. Police said the bus, which was more than 10 years old, did not have enough power to climb the mountain road and slid back, tumbling into the valley. The bus was carrying the Taiwanese passengers to a mountain stop from where they were to begin hiking, police said. There were no foreigners on the bus.
