<HEAD>One New York Beach Blood Vial Infected With AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of three vials that washed ashore last week on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> beaches contained human blood infected with the AIDS virus, state Health Commissioner Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON> said today. <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON> said the sample, discovered on <LOCATION> Lido </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> about 20 miles east of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, also tested positive for hepatitis at the state <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> laboratory in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>. Another vial, found on a beach about 40 miles east of the city, contained blood that tested both positive and negative for the virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome, <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON> said. A third vial tested negative, the health commissioner said. <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON> said the chances of beachgoers getting infected with the AIDS virus or hepatitis, by either stepping on the vials and being cut by broken glass or from blood spilled on the beach or in the water, are `` remote.'' Neither virus can survive for long outside the human body, and the sample that tested positive for the AIDS virus is believed to be inactive. `` The conditions to which the infected samples were exposed almost certainly destroyed most if not all the active virus,'' <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON> said. While the results `` confirm some of our fears'' about the danger of the material that washed up on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> beaches, <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON> said `` we do not feel the presence of these materials represent a significant public health hazard.'' <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON> said investigators do not yet know where the vials originated or how long they were in the water. But the commissioner said they are of a design that is `` clearly associated with the medical establishment.'' The vials could have come from a doctor's office, medical research facility or a hospital, he said. The discovery of blood samples and other medical debris temporarily closed some of <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s most popular beaches late last week in the midst of a prolonged heat wave. When the beaches reopened over the weekend, attendance was cut in half in many places. As of today, all beaches on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> were open except for a 1.4-mile stretch of <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Midland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>.
