told reporters in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. `` There may be differences of opinion. There may be agreements to disagree. All the indications that I have are whatever differences had existed, they are gradually being worked out.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was already sharpening his rhetoric in preparation for a fall campaign that continues to look like a tight battle. `` I am not the one who feels that the problems of agricultural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> can be solved by planting more Belgian endive,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told a farm meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The vice president was referring to the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor's suggestion in early 1987 in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> that crop diversification was a solution to agricultural problems, pointing to farmers' experience in his home state A tight race was the analysis from the latest <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> poll. It put <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> ahead of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> by a 47-39 margin among 947 registered voters surveyed by telephone last week. The margin of error was plus or minus three percentage points.
