<HEAD>Computer Analysis Arrives for Probe of Airbus Incident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Sub for graf 2 to state that tapes first sent to Washington
for analysis and now being returned to gulf, picks up graf 3 pvs,
``As the secrecy-shrouded, etc, 3rd graf pvs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An analysis of computer tapes from the cruiser <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> has been delivered to experts trying to reconstruct the shooting down of an Iranian jetliner, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said Tuesday. The tapes were flown to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last week for analysis at a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> laboratory in <LOCATION> Virgnia </LOCATION>. The analysis has now been flown to the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> accompanied by two specialists who will present the analysis to the six-member team of investigators. As the secrecy-shrouded inquiry entered its second week, the focus was on resolving conflicts over the altitude and other details of <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s Flight 655 just before the A300 <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> was blown apart over the Strait of <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION> on July 3, killing all 290 people aboard. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the computer analysis could prove crucial in determining whether a misreading of target data by the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION>' sophisticated Aegis air defense system led the ship's commander, Capt. <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, to fire at what he believed was an Iranian F-14 fighter. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said the Airbus was emitting a confusing mixture of identification signals, one typical of a commercial airliner and another similar to that which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships had received previously from Iranian F-14s. While the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> initially reported the jetliner at about 9,200 feet and descending to about 7,900 feet before it was hit, data from two other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships indicates it was nearer to 12,000 feet and either flying level or clim