ls said earlier that an Iranian scout plane, a U.S.-built P-3 Orion, apparently was airborne and could have monitored and relayed the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION>' warning messages to the jetliner. Iranian pilots and others have been quoted as saying the pilot of Flight 655 would have been so busy talking with controllers in <PERSON> Bandar </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION>, his destination across the gulf, that he would not necessarily have heard the cruiser's radioed warnings on the civilian radio frequency. Iranian officials have not acknowledged that the plane was transmitting a military identification signal on `` Mode 2,'' the frequency reserved for military use, as the Americans claim. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> source said the <ORGANIZATION> IFF </ORGANIZATION>, or identification friend or foe, codes used by Iranian F-14s had been given to the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> by the missile cruiser <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON>, which the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> replaced on gulf duty in late May. The Airbus' flight recorder also could provide important clues to the plane's altitude and other details, but <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s navy commander, Rear Adm. <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Hossein </PERSON> <PERSON> Malekzadegan </PERSON>, said on Monday there was no truth to reports that it had been recovered.
