prediction.'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> could still face an internal department review of his actions. Portions of <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>'s sealed report are said to question <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s candor and ethics. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had given <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> no advice on the issue. `` Those matters are all left to the incoming attorney general,'' the spokesman said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> called <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> `` the ideal choice for attorney general,'' saying that in six years as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney for western <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, he was `` a prosecutor's prosecutor ... a tough-minded crime buster.'' `` I urge the Senate to move quickly to confirm him as well as our other <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> nominees so they can roll up their sleeves and get to work enforcing the laws of the land,'' the president said. Also awaiting <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation are the deputy attorney general, <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Christensen </PERSON>; the No. 3 person in the department, Associate Attorney General <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Keating </PERSON>; and the criminal division chief, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Christensen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> have been on the job since early June; <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> has been at work about a month longer. All were appointed on an acting basis by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Christensen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> are replacing former Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> and Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Weld </PERSON>, whose protest resignations March 29 over <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s continued tenure brought accusations of a serious leadership gap in the department. As a <LOCATION> U.S. </