<FIRST>u w AM-Cities-Aid     07-12 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cities-Aid,630,</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cities Increased Fees, Raised Taxes In Face Of Federal Aid
Cutbacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's cities, encumbered by burgeoning budget gaps spawned by federal aid cutbacks, sharply increased local fees this fiscal year and many also raised property taxes, a study reported Tuesday. Over half the country's major cities face potential deficits, although some will be able to dip into reserves to avoid finishing the year in the red, said the study by the National League of Cities. `` The present trends are dangerous and potentially devastating,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Beals </PERSON>, executive director of the league, a national organization of local governments. <PERSON> Beals </PERSON> called the nation's domestic policies on cities `` indifferent at best and destructive at worst.'' The league report, titled `` City Fiscal Conditions in 1988,'' describes how 347 communities _ from large cities such as <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to smaller towns like <LOCATION> Yankton </LOCATION>, S.D. _ are coping with the end, two years ago, of the federal revenue sharing program. The survey found that 67 percent increased existing fees and charges for city services in the 1988 fiscal year, while 44 percent reduced spending this year on capital construction projects. Fifty-five percent cut back the growth of their operating budgets and 41 percent raised property taxes. Those figures were higher than 1987, when 58 percent raised fees and 38 percent raised property taxes over the year before. In addition, 37 percent of the cities said they had instituted new fees. Another 14 percent reduced city services. Cities overwhelmingly cited federal cutbacks as the reason for their budgetary straits. Almost half of the cities that cut services said less federal money was the main reason, and 64 percent of those who scaled back capital projects cited the loss of revenue sharing. `` The backbone of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> _ our cities and towns _ is bending under an increasing load,'' <PERSON> Beals </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` Whether this burden will continue to grow more cumbersome, or whether it will be relieved through a more responsible set of national policies is one of the urgent questions of the 1988 elections and for the next administration,'' <PERSON> Beals </PERSON> said at a news conference on the report. The news conference was held as word came that <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the likely Democratic presidential nominee, had picked Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> as his running mate. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> heads the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and has worked with the league on a number of issues affecting the nation's cities, <PERSON> Beals </PERSON> noted. `` We found him to be very open-minded and responsive -LRB- and he has -RRB- given us a very sympathetic hearing,'' <PERSON> Beals </PERSON> said. The report measured spending estimates for the 1988 fiscal year _ the 12-month period that ended June 30 _ which the report acknowledged are not yet final. It said 50 percent of the cities expect expenditures to exceed revenues in 1988, but noted that cities usually are pessimistic in such projections. The actual percentage of cities that finish their fiscal years with deficits is expected to be lower, since municipalities facing shortfalls dip into reserves carried over from previous years to balance their budgets, the report said. In 1987, 33 percent of the cities surveyed by the league actually reported shortfalls, down from 40 percent in 1986. More than half those cities had surpluses in 1986 and 1987, but only 24 percent said they expect to take in more than they spend in the 1988 fiscal year. The survey also found that 25 percent of the cities had actually seen revenues from all sources decline in 1988 from last year. In other areas of spending, the survey found that 25 percent of the cities had reduced the number of city workers, 24 percent had raised or imposed new fees for developers and 22 percent had frozen municipal hiring. Eighteen percent had instituted new taxes or raised sales taxes.
</TEXT>
