<HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Five US Envoys Sent Home by Host Governments Since 1973</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ambassador <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Melton </PERSON>, who was ordered by the Nicaraguan government to leave the country, is believed to be the fifth <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat of his rank to be withdrawn at the request of the host government over the past 15 years. Earlier this year, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hume </PERSON> <PERSON> Horan </PERSON>, was recalled by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because of personality differences with King Fahd. Unlike <PERSON> Melton </PERSON>, however, <PERSON> Horan </PERSON> was not declared persona non grata but <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> authorities made clear the monarch's displeasure with <PERSON> Horan </PERSON>, who spent only seven months in <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. Within days after <PERSON> Horan </PERSON>'s recall, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> nominated Ambassador <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON> to replace him. The case involving <PERSON> Melton </PERSON> is believed to be the first of its kind since 1976 when the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Equatorial </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Spiro </PERSON>, was ordered out of the country. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> relations with <LOCATION> Equatorial </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> were poor at the time because of unpredictable behavior of President <PERSON> Masie </PERSON> <PERSON> Nguema </PERSON> and other factors. During that period, <PERSON> Spiro </PERSON> was the accredited ambassador to both <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Equatorial </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> but resided in <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION>. He made occasional visits to <LOCATION> Equatorial </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION>. Full relations with that country were not restored until 1979. In 1975, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinton </PERSON>, was expelled by President <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON> <PERSON> Sese </PERSON> <PERSON> Seko </PERSON> for alleged interference in <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>'s internal affairs In 1973, Jamaican Prime Minister <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> expelled Ambassador <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Deroulet </PERSON> after the envoy had said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> refrained from interfering in the 1972 national elections in <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> in return for a promise from <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> not to nationalize certain <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business investments in <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> denied the allegation.
