<HEAD>Jackson Says Not Told of Choice</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with Jackson comments; pick up 7th graf pvs
bgng ``Jackson declined...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> today called the selection of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> as <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' running mate `` a strategic move'' and said `` I'm too controlled ... to be angry'' at being passed over. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said he will support the ticket nominated at the Democratic National Convention next week but brushed off questions about whether he will campaign enthusiastically for the party. `` The approach he used today was of course a matter of his own campaign making a strategic move to solidify his organization. That is his right to do,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said at a news conference. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said he first learned of the selection from reporters who met him at an airport here this morning. He said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> later phoned him, but they did not have a lengthy discussion. Asked if he was angry, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> replied: `` No, I'm too controlled, I'm too clear, I'm too mature to be angry. I'm focused on what we must do to keep hope alive ...'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> nearly crossed paths at the airport with <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, who was preparing to leave for <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. The two did not meet. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> declined comment on most of the questions he was asked by reporters as he walked to his car at <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s National Airport. When asked if <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had informed him of a decision, he said, `` No.'' The night before, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> stated publicly for the first time that he would accept the No. 2 spot on the Democratic ticket and said he assured <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' talent scout that he would be a loyal vice president. But <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> stopped short Monday night of pledging loyalty if he is not chosen for the ticket. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told reporters that would depend on discussions yet to be held between him and the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor, the certain nominee when <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> convene in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> next week. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> met with reporters after a two-hour private session here Monday as <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> neared the end of the running mate search for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who has said repeatedly he had earned serious consideration for the No. 2 spot, previously had demurred at saying whether he would accept a bid. He joked to a farm group before the job interview, `` So far <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has not accepted my offer and I have not refused his.'' But there were no jokes after the session with <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s second interview for the job. `` If it was offered to me, I would accept it,'' he said. `` If it's not offered to me, then how I respond will be based upon many things that we've not yet discussed.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who technically remains in contention for the Democratic nomination even though <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has a numerical lock on a first-ballot victory at the convention, said, `` We intend to have an effective, informative convention that would inspire our nation, unify our party and take us to victory.'' He said they did not discuss outstanding differences on the party platform. He said he gave <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> `` my candid views as to the office of the vice presidency and shared with him, when asked, what I thought my qualifications to be and my vision of that role.'' <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> called it `` an excellent meeting ... very productive. It served the purpose for which it was intended, and that is to continue and to conclude the background check phase of the selection process.'' <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON>, who flew back to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> Monday night, said, `` I plan to review my meeting with Reverend <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> with the governor, and then it's up to the governor.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> adviser <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, who took part in the meeting, told reporters that although <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> did not say when <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would announce his decision, `` I got the impression it was going to be very soon ... in the next couple of days.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, asked to rate his chances, said, `` There is no way of judging that.'' Asked if the interview could have been a charade, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said: `` I have no basis to challenge the intergrity of Mr. <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> or Gov. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. If this is just a charade, it is a great waste of their time, at a time when time is precious.'' Asked if he would consider having his name placed in nomination for vice president if <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> chooses someone else, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said, `` That's not under consideration.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, asked if <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> had asked him to promise loyalty to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, said: `` He did ask it. The answer is yes because that's the right thing to do. But <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> made clear he was only talking about loyalty as a running mate. He said they talked about not only the requirements of the vice presidency, but `` the latitude. No one, of course, would be asked to do anything illegal or unconstitutional.'' `` So long as there is room for serious discussion, debate and deliberation, maturity requires that you agree to agree -LRB- and -RRB- that you agree to disagree. ... `` said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. On `` your best day, your point of view may prevail. At your worst, your point of view simply may be a matter of influence. `` I'm one to support the party. I've done that down through the years.'' Earlier, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said, `` If I am not on the team, then the governor must determine who the team members are and what role they will play.'' He said he was seeking `` a partnership of equity and shared responsibility.'' Asked how his followers would respond if he is left off the ticket, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said: `` Let's take it one day at a time. My constituency is tough and matured, enduring, loyal but also responsible as it seeks its rightful place in our party's leadership It has earned partnership in our party.''
