<HEAD>Cuauhtemoc Cardenas: Famous Name, Charismatic Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Mexico-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Although he may lose the election, opposition candidate <PERSON> Cuauhtemoc </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> appears to have secured a position as the rallying point for the discontent with the party that has ruled <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> for 59 years. Whether he won the presidential election or not is still a matter of heated debate. He says he did, the governing <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>, says he did n't. Privately, top <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> officials admit <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> won the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>, the core of the sprawling <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> metropolitan area, and three of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s 31 states. Even those victories would be a stunning blow to the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>, which has won every presidential race since its founding in 1929 with at least 70 percent of the vote, and never has lost a senate or gubernatorial race. <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> claimed Monday he won 39 percent of the vote nationwide to <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> candidate <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>'s 35 percent. After a week's delay and opposition charges of fraud, the government has only provided partial returns on the race for the lower house of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Figures released Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> say <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> had 53.59 percent of the votes counted. <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> was second with 26.08 percent, and <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON> of the conservative <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> followed with 16.04 percent. Even these figures, which the opposition disputes, would be an astonishing feat for <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>, a candidate who in December started to build his predominantly leftist coalition from a tiny base. His campaign was considered unlikely to shake the foundations of power, and ruling politicians dismissed him as a candidate of `` nostalgia'' who was trading on his famous name. Through it all, the charismatic candidate never lost his composure. Before hundreds of thousands of adoring supporters on the campaign trail, in the steamy battle over vote fraud, at middle-of-the-night news conferences in the days-long wait for the returns, he was always calm, always reasonable. While <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON> barreled down the campaign trail, blustering about civil disobedience, <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> quietly counseled restraint and spoke of using the force of law. <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>, 54, spent the day before the election in the central state of <LOCATION> Michoacan </LOCATION>, where he once was the governing <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>'s governor. He was n't basking in the warmth accorded a favorite son. He was mourning his old friend and political strategist, <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Xavier </PERSON> <PERSON> Ovando </PERSON>, gunned down while on the way home from a political strategy session. `` <PERSON> Xavier </PERSON> has fallen because he was fighting for <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to have a true and authentic democracy,'' <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> said. `` He died because he dreamed of a better, an independent and a free <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>.'' That moment was like a snapshot capturing the campaign and the candidate. <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> was criticized for wanting to turn the clock back to 1910, when the Mexican Revolution started with the promise of a better life, or to 1938, when his father, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s revered 20th century president, nationalized <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s oil and handed the young republic its pride. But the <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> message was n't about the nuts and bolts of governing. It was visceral: He became a focal point of discontent with a system that seemed calcified by nearly 60 years of single-party rule. It was an ironic role for politician who once seemed to be the ultimate product of a system his father, the late President <PERSON> Lazaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>, helped create. <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> flourished in the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>. He was its governor in <LOCATION> Michoacan </LOCATION> and also a senator. The break started last year when <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> seemed to sense the growing force of a cold wind of disfavor that was about to blast the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>. Calling his movement the Democratic Current, he told the party to hold a presidential primary. The traditionalists in the party refused and <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> defected, forming a left-of-center coalition, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. When he decided to run for president he campaigned virtually without a critical forum _ television. TV in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is government-controlled or pro-government. But as he traveled the nation, he gathered larger and larger crowds, winning the support of peasants, students, the struggling middle class, intellectuals and oil workers. About a month before the election, he did what was considered impossible _ he unified the left. The candidate of the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the largest organized leftist force, dropped out and endorsed <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>. No one knows if that political unity will survive once the campaign passions cool. But <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> now appears to command a popular force the governing party can not ignore.
