 that he'd offered him the vice presidency and how he could get out of it,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` One of the major factors ultimately that persuaded him that he should take him was the fact that he would be so mean as majority leader that it was much better having him as vice president, where you could control him, than to have him as majority leader. Particularly after you had offered him the job, then it would have been disastrous to have that affront and withdraw it.'' The two <PERSON> Kennedys </PERSON> decided to try and have <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> take himself out. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> said he made two trips to <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s hotel room. On the first, he said, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s close friend, House Speaker <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Rayburn </PERSON>, was there and <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> only tried to feel <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> out. But, like everything else about that time, there are different versions of that meeting. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, the late publisher of the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> who was close to <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, recalled these events in a famous memorandum that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> recently studied during his search for a vice president. `` <ORGANIZATION> LBJ </ORGANIZATION> seemed about to jump out of his skin,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> wrote of the first Lyndon-Bobby meeting. `` He shouted at me that <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> had just come in and told <PERSON> Rayburn </PERSON> and him that there was such opposition and that <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> should withdraw for the sake of the party.'' On the second visit, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said, he and <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> were alone. It was 2:30 p.m. on the last day of the convention. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> said he conveyed two thoughts he'd worked out with his brother. That there would be an unpleasant fight by labor leaders if <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> were on the ticket and that <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> wanted him to play an important role, running the party, and thereby build the machinery he could use to run for president in 1968. `` I do n't know whether it was just an act or anything,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> told <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON>. `` But he just shook, and tears came into his eyes, and he said, ` I want to be vice president, and if the president will have me, I'll join with him in making a fight for it.' `` I said, ` well, that's fine. He wants you to be vice president if you want to be vice president, we want you to know.''' At this point, too, there are conflicting accounts. <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> remembered returning to his brother who said he had been advised that vaccilation on the vice president was disastrous and that he would announce <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> as the choice. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Deal </LOCATION> lawyer in <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s camp recalled that at the end of the first meeting <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> called <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> who told him: `` <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON>'s not up to date, I've already announced that <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> is the candidate.'
