<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sixteen lawyers for people and companies in the defense procurement probe are demanding that the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> launch an investigation into the sources of leaks to the press. A department official said Tuesday it is `` too early'' to decide whether to do so. `` We are writing to you to request that you commence an investigation and take appropriate remedial action to deal with the virtual flood of leaks by <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> employees involved in or privy to the details of the investigation,'' the attorneys said in their unusual letter. One lawyer called the joint effort `` extraordinary.'' The letter, dated July 8 and publicly released Tuesday, was addressed to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaheen </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Office of Professional Responsibility. It complained that `` frequency and substance of these ` leaks' is ... unprecedented.'' <PERSON> Shaheen </PERSON>, who has responsibility for investigating ethics cases involving <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> employees, refused to comment. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, a department spokesman, said it was `` too early to determine that we will undertake an investigation.'' Several of the defense counsels are former assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys, obviously taking advantage of their knowledge of internal <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> procedures to stop what they feel is a case of government officials trying their case in the newspapers and on television. Justice investigators have `` knowingly ensured dissemination of confidential information and sensationalization of the entire investigation'' by leaking information, the