<DATELINE>PRESTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Amish man jailed for refusing to display an orange slow-moving-vehicle sign on his horse-drawn buggy was exempted from wearing the orange jump suit normally worn by inmates. <PERSON> Gideon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hershberger </PERSON>, 62, served seven days in the Fillmore County Jail for contempt of court and was released Tuesday. <PERSON> Hershberger </PERSON> and other Amish contend that displaying the orange signs is against their religion. `` I'd say it's the most I can do,'' he said. `` I do n't want to be stubborn, but I will continue without the sign. What else can I do?'' County Sheriff <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Gudmundson </PERSON> allowed <PERSON> Hershberger </PERSON> to wear his blue denim pants, deep blue cotton shirt and navy blue suspenders. District Court Judge <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> ruled earlier this month that public safety overrides the Amish resistance to the orange triangle. `` Religion is not a defense in this case,'' she said. <PERSON> Hershberger </PERSON> said the Amish prefer to trust God over worldly symbols, and they want to live the way their forefathers lived. Some Amish use orange triangles. But others use a black triangle with a white outline and some of the older, more conservative members like <PERSON> Hershberger </PERSON> use no sign at all. They prefer to outline their buggies with white reflective tape. <PERSON> Hershberger </PERSON> spent his jail time working in a woodworking shop and reading. <PERSON> Gudmundson </PERSON> is sympathetic to <PERSON> Hershberger </PERSON> and other Amish violators. `` They say they do n't want to create problems for me or the state, which they are,'' he said. `` But this is something I admire them for, even though I ca n't agree with it.''
