<HEAD>Armenian Enclave Votes to Secede</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 23d graf `Medvedev said' to CORRECT to telephone
interview, not television</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislators of a mountain enclave that has been involved in an ethnic tug-of-war for months voted Tuesday to secede from <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and join <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> _ a dramatic first in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> politics, but probably futile. The legislature of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, a predominantly Armenian enclave in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, was unanimous except for one abstention in the decision to secede and rename the area the <ORGANIZATION> Artsakh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Autonomous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Region </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armenia </ORGANIZATION>, radio reporters in the territory reported. About 160,000 people live in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> and three-quarters are ethnic Armenians. Dissident historian <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> said the legislative action appears to have little chance of success. `` It's unconstitutional,'' he said. `` It can not be considered legal.'' Never before in Soviet history has a region's legislature voted to withdraw from the republic of which it is a part, he said. The decision defies central authorities all the way up to <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and tests Kremlin tolerance of assertions of rights by the country's more than 100 national groups. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has encouraged citizens to speak out under his policy of glasnost, or openness. The Soviet constitution gives citizens the right to self-determination, but also requires that a republic consent to any change in its boundaries. <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> is an autonomous region of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, which is Soviet <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s neighbor in the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION>. Its legislature asked Feb. 20 that the Azerbaijani and Armenian governments approve the transfer to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. The Armenians agreed June 15 but <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>'s legislature rejected the request two days later. Strikes and street rallies have disrupted <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>, the territorial capital, for weeks. A statement by the legislature, read over the telephone by reporters for the <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> radio station, said: `` The Soviet of People's Deputies of the <ORGANIZATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Autonomous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Region </ORGANIZATION> declares its secession from the <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Socialist </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>.'' Armenians, most of whom are Christians, consider <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> part of their ancestral homeland but in 1923 the region was assigned to <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, which is predominantly Moslem. The dispute began with demonstrations by Armenians in both <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> itself in February and ethnic riots were reported in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, an <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> port. Officials said 32 people were killed _ 26 Armenians and six <LOCATION> Azerbaijanis </LOCATION> _ and 200 injured. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told a national <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference June 28 the powers of the country's 15 republics and other ethnic entities should be expanded, but said some ethnic minorities were going too far. `` Some think that any questions, from the redrawing of borders to the establishment of opposition parties, can be resolved'' through glasnost, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> believes such abuses of democratization run counter to the task of perestroika, contradict the people's interests,'' he said Perestroika, or restructuring, is what <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> calls his plans for social and economic reform. <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> rejected the territorial demand in February, but said living conditions in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> would be improved. The Kremlin approved a multimillion-dollar package of social and cultural improvements for the region in March, but strikes and demonstrations continued. After <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> rejected the transfer request, <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>'s legislature proposed a compromise: putting the region under temporary control of the central government in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Armenian delegates to the party conference in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> suggested other compromises that included attaching the region to <LOCATION> Stavropol </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s home district in the Russian republic. <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>'s leaders did not budge. <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> said in a telephone interview that Tuesday's decision appeared aimed at pressuring <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> into approving the territorial transfer. Pravda, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper, said on Tuesday an `` overwhelming majority'' of Armenians who began a strike July 4 in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, the Armenian capital, had decided to return to work. Dissident journalist <PERSON> Mofses </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorgisyan </PERSON> said the walkout was gaining strength, however, and that representatives of factories in the republic of 3.4 million people reported 70 percent absenteeism Monday. He said by telephone from <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> that soldiers and tanks were deployed around the city's outskirts and militiamen patrolled inside the city limits. The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armenia </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> criticized officials throughout the republic Tuesday for `` delaying, showing carelessness and irresponsibility in the realization of practical measures aimed at improving the situation,'' the government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Gorgisyan </PERSON> said 300,000 to 400,000 people gathered outside <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ancient </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manuscripts </ORGANIZATION>, known as the Matenadaran, on Monday night to support the strike and press the territorial demand. A reporter for the republic's official news agency, Armenpress, said the number was about 100,000. <PERSON> Gorgisyan </PERSON>, 27, belongs to an underground group called the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Self-Determination </ORGANIZATION> and publishes an underground journal called Fatherland.
