<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A boy trapped for 20 hours under the rubble of a collapsed department store may lose use of his kidneys, doctors said. <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Branch </ORGANIZATION> physicians treating 9-year-old <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Mena </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Merida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, said toxins from dead muscle tissue apparently destroyed his body's ability to cleanse his blood. However, doctors said <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON>'s spunk may help him through the critical first days of what may be a months-long stay at the hospital. `` He's mad, and he's scared,'' said <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Calhoun </PERSON>, an orthopedic surgeon. <ORGANIZATION> Mena </ORGANIZATION> and a cousin who lost a leg in the accident in <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION> last week are receiving high-pressure oxygen treatments. Both are in critical condition, officials said. `` He complains the whole time he is in the -LRB- hyperbaric -RRB- chamber,'' said Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mader </PERSON>, who is overseeing <ORGANIZATION> Mena </ORGANIZATION>'s treatment at <ORGANIZATION> UTMB </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Biomedical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. `` But that's good,'' <PERSON> Mader </PERSON> said, `` because he's a fighter, and that is what it takes.'' <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON>'s mother remained hospitalized in <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION> and a 15-year-old sister, <PERSON> Mya </PERSON>, died in the accident, authorities said. The boy's father, who like his son speaks no English, lies outside the chamber window so he can look at the boy. `` They communicate over the telephone,'' <PERSON> Mader </PERSON> said. `` The father gives the boy a lot of support. Otherwise, he'd be unmanageable.'' <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON>'s cousin, <PERSON> Yvette </PERSON> <PERSON> Lire </PERSON>, 14, of <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION>, has shown some improvement since her right leg was amputated below the knee, <PERSON> Calhoun </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Yvette </PERSON>'s sister, <PERSON> Paloma </PERSON>, 12, died in the accident. The <ORGANIZATION> Amigo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Store </ORGANIZATION> collapsed during heavy rain Friday, killing 14 people and injuring at least 47 others. Investigators have not determined the cause.
