<FIRST>u w AM-BaseClosings     07-12 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Base Closings,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>House OKs Mechanism to Close Unneeded Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, trying to solve one of its toughest political issues, voted 374-39 Tuesday to give the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> a chance to save money by shutting down unneeded military bases. The chamber passed a complicated plan that involves having an independent commission decide which bases to close. `` For too many years, obsolete military bases have been treated as sacred cows and the country can not afford this anymore,'' Rep. <PERSON> Chalmers </PERSON> <PERSON> Wylie </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ohio </LOCATION>, told his colleagues. `` The time has come for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to stiffen its backbone.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> estimates that between $ 2 billion and $ 5 billion a year can be saved if the military is allowed to close installations it says are obsolete. But bases mean jobs and since 1977 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has enacted a stiff and complex series of laws that have prevented the Pentagon from shutting down any of the 3,800 military installations in the continental <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The plan approved Tuesday calls for a nine-member commission, which will makes its recommendations to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> by next Dec. 31. The president would then have until Jan. 16, four days before leaving office, to either accept or reject the entire list. He could not approve a partial list. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could block the closures by a majority vote in both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> backs the plan and has already appointed a nine-member commission, which has been meeting for the past month. The commission will also study the 1,900 military installations maintained by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in foreign nations, but will not have authority to recommend closures there. In approving the plan, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rejected a different base-closing proposal, which would have retained a few of the current restrictions. The version approved Tuesday was first adopted on a 223-186 vote shortly before the final passage. The House action sends the bill to a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION> to resolve differences with a Senate-passed version. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> measure was approved as an amendment to a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget bill, but was later dropped out of that legislation. In the decades after World War II, when the nation was winding down from its large military structure, the Pentagon was usually allowed to what it wanted on the issue, with the exception of a handful of bases protected by key members. Between 1961 and 1977, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> shut down 3,600 installations. But in 1975, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> proposed shutting down <ORGANIZATION> Loring </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in northern <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. That state's legislators blocked the move by requiring lengthy _ and costly _ environmental impact studies for the <PERSON> Loring </PERSON> closure and all future closings. Rep. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Armey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, chief sponsor of the base-closing plan, said the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> action `` will go a long way toward cutting fat instead of muscle from our national defense.'' <PERSON> Armey </PERSON>'s plan was rejected a year ago, 199-192, but he offered the proposal again because he argued that a lame-duck administration might be willing to approve the unpopular cuts. Rep. <PERSON> Toby </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, R-Wis., urged approval of the bill because he said `` it's time to cut the pork out of the budget process ... it's the right thing for the country Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> AuCoin </PERSON>, D-Ore., agreed, saying: `` This whole program of bases is not a welfare program ... it's not an economic program We should have bases for one reason and one reason only _ because they serve military needs.'' In working through the bill, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted down, on a voice vote, a proposed amendment that would have required the closure of foreign bases before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases are shut down. The chamber also rejected, on another voice vote, a move that would have added four members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to the commission.
</TEXT>
