<HEAD>Defendant Blasts Arms Indictment as Coverup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A defendant in a Contra arms-smuggling indictment blasted the charges against him Tuesday as a whitewash aimed at covering up illegal activities of <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON>, a one-time mercenary who turned against the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> policy and then cooperated with investigators, said he was informed Tuesday he has been charged in a <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> indictment still sealed by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office here. The indictment handed up last month is believed to accuse a small number of men with violating the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Neutrality Act by conspiring to aid the Contras to overthrow the Nicaraguan government. `` I have some news for this administration,'' <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> said in a statement released in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` I wo n't take the fall for <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ollie </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> or <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> said the indictments were returned only because <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> got wind that <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s then-U.S. Attorney <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON> was trying to stop the investigation at the behest of Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> investigated charges that the probe was sidetracked, but did not reach any conclusion. `` Clearly, the only reason why the -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- attorney's office sought these indictments is to protect itself,'' said <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON> `` could n't admit that his investigation was a farce, and that he and his staff had participated in a coverup.'' He said he had been cooperating with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney for two years, giving information about high-level involvement in the illegal supply network, but wound up being one of the few indicted. `` That's what I call shooting the messenger,'' he said. <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON> has quit the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney's office here and will be practicing law in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. But he has previously denied charges that he stonewalled the investigation, and said a congressional committee that took testimony from prosecutors in his office failed to find evidence that he slowed the investigation at <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s request <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON>, who most recently worked for a liberal policy group in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, became a vocal opponent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy in Central America. North eventually targeted him for his anti-Contra activities, according to notes released during the Iran-Contra affair. Until he changed his mind on aid to the Contras, <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> aided Civilian Materiel Assistance in its efforts to help the Nicaraguan rebels. <ORGANIZATION> CMA </ORGANIZATION>'s head <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Posey </PERSON> has previously said he expects to be indicted along with <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON>, and has also said he was working to aid the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration.
