<FIRST>r w AM-SovietHarvest     07-12 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Harvest,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought-Crops</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bumper Grain Crop Seen For Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Weather conditions have been favorable for a bumper grain harvest in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, in contrast to damage done by heat and drought to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crops, a report by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> showed Tuesday. Precipitation was above normal in most of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> area, the report said And more than twice the amount of normal rain soaked crops in many of the other grain areas. Thus, the report said, total Soviet grain production this year continues to be forecast at 215 million metric tons, the report said. That would be the third year in a row that Soviet harvests have exceeded 200 million tons, an unprecedented string of bumper yields. It also would be the third largest Soviet grain harvest, exceeded by the record crop of 237.4 million tons in 1978 and the 1976 harverst of 223.8 million tons. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.6 bushels of wheat or 39.4 bushels of corn, as examples. Despite the bumper harvest, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> continues to import grain to help rebuild stockpiles and to make more available for an expanding livestock sector. In a related announcement, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> said the Soviets have bought an additional 350,000 tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn for delivery this year under a long-term supply agreement between the two countries. That would be about 13.8 million bushels. Corn prices have been averaging about $ 2.76 per bushel at the farm level, meaning that the sale could have a farm value of around $ 38 million. The corn is part of the grain the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is committed to buy during the fifth and final year of the agreement, which calls for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain. The pact expires Sept. 30, and there have been negotiations for a new one.
</TEXT>
