Supreme Court Judge <PERSON> Willem </PERSON> <PERSON> Human </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Transvaal </LOCATION> province, who had sentenced them, granted a temporary stay hours before the time of execution at <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> Central Prison. Defense attorneys said the trial should be reopened because some witnesses had said police forced them to give false testimony. One prosecution witness, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Manete </PERSON>, wrote to <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> last week that he was assaulted and threatened by police to falsely identify two of the accused as being at the scene of <PERSON> Dlamini </PERSON>'s death. He said other state witnesses also were `` unhappy with their testimony'' against the <ORGANIZATION> Sharpeville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Six </ORGANIZATION> and begged <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> to stop the executions. Judge Human decided June 13 not to reopen the case because, he said, the court had not relied solely on the suspect witnesses' testimony He added that allegations of police influence on other prosecution witnesses were `` absurd.'' He gave the defendants until July 19 to challenge the death sentences in the <ORGANIZATION> Appellate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, which had upheld his decision not to reopen the trial. Some South African commentators have suggested the intense international campaign on behalf of the defendants makes it more difficult for <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> to grant clemency because he may appear to be giving in to foreign pressure. <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Mokgesi </PERSON>, whose brother <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> is one of those condemned, met with Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> on Tuesday. She promised that to make another appeal for clemency if the high court upholds the death sentences. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZAT