<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Bill Altering Budget Process</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved legislation Tuesday that would change the oft-criticized federal budget process by putting it into a two-year cycle. The measure would appear to have lttle chance of being enacted this year. The proposal is a controversial one, and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has a short schedule this year because of the presidential and congressional elections. Under the bill, which was approved by a 9-0 vote, the budget resolution that charts the government's finances and the spending and tax bills that flesh out those plans would cover two years. Currently, those measures cover only one year. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would spend the second year of the new budget process reviewing spending decisions. Sen. <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, D-Ky., the measure's sponsor, and his supporters have argued that with the present single-year process, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> spends too much time bogged down on budget matters and not enough time scrutinizing its fiscal decisions `` It is not too much to ask that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the executive branch take one year in each <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to ensure that abuse is caught and dealt with before it becomes a public scandal,'' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said in a written statement. Proponents also say that with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> consistently passing spending bills late _ well into the fiscal year for much of the 1980s _ federal agencies must operate in a state of confusion over what their budgets will be. This makes planning for the agencies difficult. Such legislation has been introduced in the past. It consistently runs into opposition from lawmakers who argue that two-year budgeting would be too inflexible, making it hard to adjust to sudden emergencies or changes in the economy's performance Members of the Budget and Appropriations committees can be expected to jealously guard their legislative turf against a bill that would diminish their authority. The legislation now must be considered by the budget panel. In addition, Democrats may want to wait to see how <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, should he become president, would feel about such an alteration to the budget process.
