<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Mars     07-12 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Mars,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Launch Second Satellite in Probe of Mars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN_THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on Tuesday launched its second spacecraft in a week toward Mars in an ambitious program to unlock mysteries of the red planet and its largest moon, <LOCATION> Phobos </LOCATION>. Orange flames flared in the night sky over <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> as a <ORGANIZATION> Proton </ORGANIZATION> booster rocket sent the unmanned Phobos II vehicle on a 111 million-mile voyage to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>. Arrival is expected in January. Soviet television showed a recording during its evening news broadcast of the launch of Phobos II at 9:01 p.m. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> time -LRB- 1:01 p.m. EDT -RRB- from a pad at the Baikonur Cosmodrome on the steppes of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Phobos I was launched last Thursday and the media said its on-board navigation systems were activated the next day. Television showed flags of more than dozen nations, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, flying at Baikonur. The countries are participating in the mission that is designed to send the two space probes close to the <LOCATION> Phobos </LOCATION> moon and drop instruments onto the surface. Scientists said the mission might provide clues to how the universe was formed. They have said that if Phobos is an asteroid trapped by Mars' gravity, as many scientists believe, the probes will be able to study matter that is little changed since the infancy of the solar system billions of years ago The two Soviet spacecraft are to enter the gravitational pull of Mars in January and fall into orbit just behind Phobos for a three-month study of the Martian surface, atmosphere and magnetic field. In April, the two craft will drop out of their orbit and swoop to within 100 feet of Phobos' surface and release two 100-pound `` landers.'' In one experiment, a laser beam carried by a lander is designed to split off a tiny piece of Phobos' rocky surface and trap it for close examination. One of the landers is expected to operate for about a year in a stationary position, sending back data. The other is planned to bound like a superkangaroo about Phobos in 65-foot leaps, gathering and analyzing soil samples. Soviet scientists have said the Phobos mission is an important step toward a manned flight to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>, which they believe may be possible early in the 21st century. Officials have placed the cost of the Phobos mission at $ 480 million. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s Deep Space Network will provide radio-tracking data to help the spacecraft locate Phobos, which is only about 17 miles in diameter.
