<HEAD>Pollsters On Bentsen: Helps in Texas, Unknown Elsewhere</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New graf 3 with ABC-Post poll</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> will help the Democratic ticket in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, but outside his home state he is virtually unknown to most voters and may have little effect on the presidential race, pollsters said Tuesday. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> has scored low in polls on potential running mates for Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. In a <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> survey last week, only 3 percent of Democratic primary voters picked <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> from seven choices. In an <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> poll completed Monday, less than one-half of 1 percent named <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> as their choice as a running mate for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. The telephone survey of 1,100 registered voters conducted July 6-11 had a margin of error of plus or minus 3.5 percentage points. But <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' choice of <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> likely was based on a more practical measure than name recognition, pollsters said. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> gives <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> a shot to win <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and its 29 electoral votes, third-largest of any state. `` It's a high-risk technique. You've got to beat <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in his home state,'' said <PERSON> Claibourne </PERSON> <PERSON> Darden </PERSON>, an Atlanta-based pollster. `` If <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> can do that, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will be whupped.'' A statewide poll in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> in mid-June had <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> trailing Vice President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who maintains an apartment in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, by 23 points. But when <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was proposed as <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' running mate, the Democrats trailed by just 5 points. Adding <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> `` makes <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> a competitive state,'' said <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Coker </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Mason-Dixon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, which did that poll. `` If there's a drawback, it's that <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> does n't guarantee <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. That makes it risky for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>.'' Outside his state, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> is unlikely either to help or hurt <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, barring any damaging disclosures, political pollsters said. In the absence of controversy about a running mate, they said, voters tend to focus on the top of the ticket. That was backed up by a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> poll by Mason-Dixon, conducted during the weekend, putting <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> 10 points ahead of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> as well as without him. Only with Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> as a running mate did <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> draw even with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> there, WPLG-TV in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> reported. Generally, other than in a running mate's home state, `` Everybody says the choice can hurt but not help,'' said <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>, a pollster for the <ORGANIZATION> Roper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polls </ORGANIZATION>. `` Unless there's something really negative, I do n't think the vice presidential candidate matters in people's minds one way or the other.'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> thus far barely is in the public's mind. In a national Gallup poll in mid-May, 77 percent of respondents said they had not heard enough about him to have an opinion of him. Of the rest, 15 percent rated him positively, 9 percent negatively. Similarly, in a Harris poll in early May, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> ranked fifth of eight choices for a vice presidential candidate, far behind leaders <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. In the Gallup poll, a gauge that took negative ratings into account put <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> on top. `` There are many other vice presidential possibilities that are more popular than <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugick </PERSON>, a Gallup pollster. `` Basically the guy just does not have much name recognition on a national scale.'' Still, pollsters noted, many other vice presidential candidates have been little-known _ Democrat <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferraro </PERSON> in 1984, Republican <PERSON> Spiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON> in 1968 and Republican <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> in 1964, for example _ and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> himself was unknown by 77 percent of the public as recently as November. Where he is known, in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was rated favorably by 55 percent of respondents to the Mason-Dixon poll last month, and unfavorably by 12 percent. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had the same favorable rating but much higher unfavorables, 33 percent. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was rated favorably by 39 percent, unfavorably by 29 percent. In his <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> re-election contest, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> led Republican challenger Rep. <PERSON> Beau </PERSON> <PERSON> Boulter </PERSON> by 60-27; even if <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> runs for vice president and for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> at the same time, respondents said, they would favor him by 58-27. <PERSON> Coker </PERSON> noted that the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> numbers well may change, at least in part because many Texans may not have taken the suggestion of <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> for vice president seriously. Such apparently was the case with pollsters themselves. <PERSON> Hugick </PERSON> noted that Gallup just completed a poll during the weekend that tested two possible <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> running mates _ <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. `` We picked the wrong Southerner,'' he said.
