no right to expel a diplomat assigned to the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> and said it was the first case in <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> history in which a diplomat accredited to that body has been ordered out of the country. But he stopped short of saying he would fight the expulsion order, saying that he had to consult first with his government. <PERSON> Tunnermann </PERSON> said that Under Secretary of State <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> had told him he had engaged in activities as <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> ambassador which violate diplomatic norms. When <PERSON> Tunnermann </PERSON> demanded that <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> present proof, he quoted <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> as saying, `` Well, some day.'' Later, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> deputy spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Tunnermann </PERSON> had engaged in an abuse of his `` privileges of residence'' of residence in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. She said that Major <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Sampson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendoza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s military attache who also was on the list of those expelled, was guilty of the same offense. Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> declined to specify what abuses <LOCATION> Tunnermann </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Sampson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendoza </PERSON> had committed. When reminded by reporters that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had described the expulsions as retaliation, she said the diplomats were being ordered out both as a retaliatory measure and for the alleged abuses. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., said that in a meeting that he and other congressmen had with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, national security adviser <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <