<HEAD>House Panel Hears Complaints Over Refuge Expansion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Studds </PERSON>, D-Mass., Tuesday called a dispute over the current expansion plan for the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION> a `` tempest in a salt marsh'' and ordered further examination of the proposal <PERSON> Studds </PERSON>' comments came at a hearing of the Subcommittee on Fisheries and Wildlife Conservation and the Environment which examined a proposal to double the size of the refuge. The 21,662 acre tract of land and water was set aside by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> 16 years ago to protect remnant tidal wetlands and their indigenous species at the south end of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> in northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Last December President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed into law, legislation authorizing additional appropriations to complete acquisition of the original bondaries of the refuge. But administration officials Tuesday opposed the purchase of 20,850 acres of `` seasonal wetlands'' and `` salt ponds.'' The administration `` does not believe additional land purchases are warranted at this time,'' especially in light of the $ 13.1 million already spent on land acquisition, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepherd </PERSON>, vice president and land manager of <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Salt </PERSON>, which owns 85 percent of the land slated for purchase, argued that landowners were not told of the proposed annexation until they saw their property on a map. Although the legislation states that additions to the refuge may only be acquired from willing sellers, <PERSON> Shepherd </PERSON> said this type of notice was `` tantamount to having a federal lein on the property.'' But Mayor <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> supported the legislation saying the so-called `` condemnation'' clause which outlines how the land purchases must be made solves many of the problems cited by opponents. However <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> noted that the expansion plans would absorb almost half of his city's land, including a section earmarked for industrial development by city planners. `` <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>'s residential development is virtually in place. We need additional industrial development to complement it,'' he said. `` One section -LRB- scheduled for purchased -RRB- is 44 percent of my city. `` Anytime the federal government draws a line on a map and says this is what we designate as a refuge,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> added, `` that land becomes holy ground and it becomes impossible to develop it for any other prupose in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area.'' `` I think he's wrong,'' <PERSON> Morrision </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. `` I just have failed in convincing him, and I do n't know why. If he keeps rigid control over how the land is used he wo n't have any trouble. `` Like the chairman said, it's just a tempest in a salt marsh,'' <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> said.
