<HEAD>LaserPhotos ATH1,2,6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities said Tuesday the terrorists who attacked a Greek cruise ship may have been pro-Iranian Arabs trying to hijack it, and released photographs of three men and a woman allegedly involved. The terrorists, who apparently boarded as passengers, fired automatic weapons and hurled grenades Monday on the City of <LOCATION> Poros </LOCATION>, which was taking 471 foreign tourists on a one-day cruise through the Greek islands. City coroner <PERSON> Manolis </PERSON> <PERSON> Nonas </PERSON> reported 10 people dead and harbor officials said another body had been found, but the <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> put the toll at nine dead and 98 injured. There was no explanation for the discrepancies in the death count. Several survivors and a harbor official said Tuesday the attackers joined fleeing passengers in jumping from the ship and were picked up with them by vessels that rushed to aid the City of <LOCATION> Poros </LOCATION>. Two French survivors, not identified, appeared on state television and one said: `` We saw them jumping out of the ship, and a number of other passengers said they saw the terrorists aboard the rescue boats going to <LOCATION> Piraeus </LOCATION>.'' Police had said Monday night the terrorists escaped on a waiting speedboat. Police officials would not comment about the reports Tuesday. Officials also made conflicting statements about the number of people involved in the attack, for which no group has claimed responsibility. A senior officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Piraeus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harbor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> said the attack might be linked to the trial in <LOCATION> Piraeus </LOCATION>, scheduled for this week, of <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON>, a Palestinian wanted by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the 1982 bombing of a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> jet over <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. The officer spoke on condition of anonymity. `` We theorize they were going to seize the ship together with the people who died in the car explosion, maybe to force the freeing of the Palestinian on trial'' the officer said. <PERSON> Anastasios </PERSON> <PERSON> Sehiotis </PERSON>, minister of public order, released the photos and told reporters: `` These pictures are being circulated to all airports, harbors and border entry points. These people were involved with yesterday's attack.'' <PERSON> Sehiotis </PERSON> also indicated an explosion earlier Monday that killed two men in a car was linked to the ship attack. The car blew up near the Trocadero Marina, home dock of the City of <LOCATION> Poros </LOCATION>, and the ship was attacked about six hours later, at 8:40 p.m. The minister would give no further information except for the names of `` two Lebanese men being sought as involved in this attack.'' He identified them as <PERSON> Hamoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamid </PERSON>, 36, who rented the car, and <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Zozad </PERSON>, 21, thought to be one of the men on the ship. <PERSON> Sehiotis </PERSON> said both had been in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> since May. The two other men were not identified and it was not clear whether they were on the ship. The woman in the photo was not identified, but the picture appeared to have been taken aboard the vessel. Survivors said they saw three attackers, one masked with a stocking, fire at people on the ship and hurl several hand grenades. The explosions started a fire that brought the sun deck crashing down on passengers in the lounge below. But the <ORGANIZATION> Piraeus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harbor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> officer said he believed the attack was carried out by two men and two women who boarded the cruise ship when it called at the island of <LOCATION> Aegina </LOCATION>. He said survivors identified <PERSON> Zozad </PERSON> in one of the photographs and recognized the young woman in the other photograph released by the ministry. `` One woman, we think, had a Moroccan passport and the other a French passport. We think they found out about the car explosion and decided to shoot up the ship,'' the officer said. In <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, a woman was quoted as saying she was the mother of the French woman identified in one photograph. The woman, who identified herself only as Mrs. <PERSON> Bismuth </PERSON>, called the Agence France-Presse news agency and said she saw the picture on the Tuesday evening news. She was quoted as saying her daughter, <PERSON> Isabelle </PERSON>, 21, was a secretary vacationing in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and not a terrorist. Mrs. <PERSON> Bismuth </PERSON> said she has n't heard from her daughter since the attack, the agency reported. A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said 23 people remained hospitalized Tuesday. Seven Americans were on the cruise, but none was among the injured, the spokesman said. Greek state-run TV said an American identified as <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> was killed, but the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said they were unaware of any such person. Palestinian terrorists hijacked the Italian cruise ship <PERSON> Achille </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON> during a <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> cruise in October 1985 and killed a 69-year-old American passenger, <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Klinghoffer </PERSON>. Italian courts convicted seven Palestinians. <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON>, 34, was scheduled for trial Wednesday on charges of entering the country with a forged passport, but prison officials said it would be postponed because of a nationwide work slowdown by prison guards. The government says it is considering a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> extradition request for Rashid. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON> put a bomb on a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> plane that exploded on a Tokyo-Honolulu flight in April 1982, killing a Japanese teen-ager and wounding 15 people. He was arrested at the <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> airport June 1. Police said the car that exploded contained automatic weapons, hand grenades and ammunition and a large amount of explosives. A police spokesman, speaking privately, said an Iranian magazine also was found in the wreckage. He said a Beretta automatic pistol and fragments of Soviet-made hand grenades found on the City of <LOCATION> Poros </LOCATION> `` were identical with weapons recovered from the car wreckage.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said only two of the bodies had been identified _ <PERSON> Antonis </PERSON> <PERSON> Demaizis </PERSON>, 45, the ship's first mate, and <PERSON> Klaus </PERSON> <PERSON> Johan </PERSON> <PERSON> Grabas </PERSON>, a 33-year-old Danish tourist. The ship carried 22 crew members.
