<HEAD>Soviet Army Deserter Is Pardoned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet soldier who deserted in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> five years ago, went to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and was jailed when he returned to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, has been freed, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday. The state-run news agency said <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> was released from a labor camp under an amnesty announced on July 4 for soldiers who turned against their country during the Soviet army's 8 -LCB- - year intervention in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> In a January 1985 dispatch, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said that after <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> deserted, he was drugged, nearly starved and visited by lovers of both sexes with <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> links in an attempt to get him to make anti-Soviet statements. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said at that time that <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> left a military construction unit in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in June 1983, was brought to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> by rebels and given three choices: slander the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>; be executed, or be sent to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> where, as a deserter he was told, no mercy would be shown. At a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> news conference in 1984, <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> said he deserted because he was tired of the `` dirty war'' in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, where Soviet troops battled anti-Marxist rebels. In December 1984, he went to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Embassy </LOCATION> and asked to go home. His request was granted. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> did not say then what became of <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON>, but on Tuesday it quoted a report in the weekly newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Literaturnaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION> that he was in a labor camp. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> told the newspaper `` he felt much easier in a -LRB- labor -RRB- colony than in alien <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, that he felt calm,'' according to <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. The newspaper wrote that <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON>'s release shows fear of punishment should not deter Soviet deserters from returning home. Soviet solders entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979, replaced one pro-Soviet government with another and stayed in the country to help fight Islamic insurgents. The troops began withdrawing May 15.
