<HEAD>Woman Who Tended Husband's Corpse Regains Custody of Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALESBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman who was accused of child neglect after authorities discovered she had been tending her husband's corpse nearly nine years has regained custody of her children <ORGANIZATION> Knox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> restored <PERSON> Carole </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>' parental rights following a review of several psychological examinations conducted on the children, a 17-year-old girl and a 14-year-old boy <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> said the children could return to their mother's home, where the mummified corpse of <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> was found Jan. 29 _ nearly nine years after his death. An autopsy revealed that <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, who was a diabetic, died May 12, 1979, at age 39. His brown and shriveled corpse was discovered in the family home where Mrs. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, 42, had kept it bathed and clothed. Mrs. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, a registered nurse, had tended the corpse with the help of her two children and a house guest, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunce </PERSON>. Authorities said the family's beliefs in a holistic health cult led them to believe they could communicate with <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> through the body and that he would return to life. On Feb. 1, Mrs. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kunce </PERSON> both pleaded guilty in <ORGANIZATION> Knox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to a charge of failing to report the death. <PERSON> Kunce </PERSON> later changed his plea to innocent. They also were charged with felony forgery. Mrs. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> was accused of fabricating a power of attorney for her dead husband in 1984 and using it to refinance a home mortgage. <PERSON> Kunce </PERSON> was charged with forgery for signing his name to the document as a witness. Mrs. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> pleaded guilty to the forgery charge and was granted probation. She was ordered to submit to psychiatric treatment. In a separate civil case, Mrs. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> admitted she was guilty of child neglect for allowing her children to live with the corpse. The children were placed in foster care upon discovery of the body.
