<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> told the largest black sorority on Tuesday that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s $ 152 billion trade deficit can be blamed on the nation's failure to cooperate with business people of different races around the globe. `` We have a trade deficit because we in big business are still uncomfortable if the environment is dominated by people of color,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> told about 4,000 members of <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sigma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sorority </ORGANIZATION>. `` If we are going to end the trade deficit without death and conflict, it will be when blacks and whites, male and female, young and old, <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> and Jew are able to work together,'' said <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. The ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> during the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration urged members of the world's largest organization of college-educated black women to extend the `` sisterhood and teamwork you enjoy in this sorority to the sisters organizing mine workers and domestic servants in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' Delta was founded at <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1913 and has about 125,000 members. It's holding its 75th anniversary through Wednesday at the Civic Auditorium.
