<HEAD>Grosz Appeals For Public Support of Stringent Economic Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and government leader, <PERSON> Karoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, appealed on Tuesday for public support of a stringent economic program and harshly criticized the work of his government over the past year. `` What lies ahead are sacrifices for the sake of the future,'' <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> said on an evening televisoin interview. He said it could take 10 to 15 years for his program to show results. It was the first time a Hungarian government chief has evaluated his first year in office. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> said he was `` very dissatisfied'' with the achievements of the last 12 months despite the efforts to implement a program of austerity measures and economic restructuring introduced last year. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> said the government, economic experts and individual citizens `` have not been working efficiently enough.'' The 20-minute interview was conducted on the eve of a meeting of the party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that is to discuss two alternative economic programs. One would push through radical reforms towards a more market-oriented economy. This, however, could lead to 80,000 to 100,000 unemployed and result in greater social tensions. The second would introduce changes more gradually. The party newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Nepszabadsag </ORGANIZATION> published details of the proposals on Saturday, the first time the agenda of a <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meeting was published in advance in such detail. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> said economic restructuring would mean hard times for Hungarians, as it aims to stop the growth of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s foreign debt, now totaling $ 18 billion, by 1990. The government this year introduced <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s first value-added and personal income tax as part of its austerity program. A value-added tax is a form of indirect sales tax. `` Parliament and the people are increasingly impatient, and there is increasing social pressure on the government to do better,'' <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> said. He appealed to Hungarians to `` understand the need'' for the program which will include curbs on imports, cuts in subsidies to loss-making firms and bankruptcy proceedings for those companies which continue to lose money. Unemployment already is to affect about 50,000 people this year. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> said the leadership planned to push ahead with its program `` and is ready to face any tensions that might be involved.'' He said steps will be taken that `` will strike hard at some sections of society,'' but that he could `` not afford to be indulgent.'' He said more attention should be devoted to industries with a future, such as telecommunications and tourism.
