<HEAD>Casino Agrees To $100,000 Settlement In Underage Gambling
Complaint</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Caesars Hotel Casino agreed Tuesday to donate $ 100,000 to two state hospitals as a precedent-setting settlement in a case involving civil charges that the gaming hall allowed a teen-age girl to gamble. Caesars will donate $ 50,000 each to the <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Edison </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Marlboro </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Marlboro </LOCATION>, both of which have facilities to treat compulsive gambling. The settlement involved a complaint that the gaming hall treated a 16-year-old girl as a high roller, offering her complimentary drinks, a hotel room, meals and show tickets. Debra <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, now 18, pleaded guilty in January to underage gambling and agreed to attend Gamblers Anonymous meetings as part of a one-year probationary sentence. State Administrative Law Judge <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> accepted the settlement on Tuesday, calling it `` novel and creative.'' <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON>, director of the state Division of Gaming Enforcement, said he was satisfied with the outcome of the complaint, which also was filed against Caesars and four other casinos. <PERSON> Elsinore </PERSON>'s Atlantis, Resorts International, <PERSON> Harrah </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Marina </PERSON> and Trump Plaza casino hotels are expected to settle their complaints by the end of this week, he said The $ 100,000 settlement is the largest that a casino has ever paid in an underage gambling offense. Prior to Tuesday's agreement, casinos paid an average of $ 2,000 per incident, <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON> said. Before the complaints were filed, <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON> said, `` The problem of juvenile gambling in this state went largely unnoticed, much less treated and remedied.'' `` Not only did the DGE complaint serve to elevate the industry's consciousness of this serious problem,'' he said, `` but the settlement we have struck today hopes to achieve some social good by dedicating substantial monies to mental health facilities in this state where compulsive gambling and other disorders may be treated. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Levenson </PERSON>, an attorney for Caesars, said the casino acknowledged that in Miss <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>'s case, `` our security force broke down ... which we have since tightened up.'' <PERSON> Levenson </PERSON> said he was hired to attend municipal court hearings to push for stiff penalties against underage gamblers who slip past the casino's security guards. `` We want to send a message out to other young people,'' <PERSON> Levenson </PERSON> said.
