<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Production of corn and other key crops is being cut severely by a nationwide drought that already ranks with the terrible burnouts of the 1930s and 1950s. While the winter wheat crop planted last fall stayed barely ahead of the drought, the later crops planted this spring have been brutalized by heat and dryness. Because it was planted last fall, winter wheat is one of the few crops for which specific per-acre production estimates are available. About 75 percent of the winter wheat has already been harvested, according to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>, and the drought loss nationally has n't been severe.
