<HEAD>The Typical Democratic Delegate: White, Middle-Aged, Well-Educated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fewer than a dozen politicians are among the delegates to the 1988 Democratic National Convention, the party's biggest political event At least that's how many own up to being politicians. An Associated Pess survey of more than 3,200 of the 4,161 delegates to the convention found that while nearly 1,000 of them hold elected offices _ including hundreds of members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and dozens of governors and mayors _ only a handful list their occupation as `` politician.'' To be exact, there are nine of them. They join nearly 300 lawyers, 100 retired people, an actor, a cook and a casket manufacturer this week as they cram into the cramped auditorium of the Omni to nominate <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for president. Of the delegates _ who hail from all 50 states, the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, and five <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territories _ the typical convention-goer is white, middle-aged and college-educated. Almost two-thirds of them have not been delegates before, the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> survey found. Their average age is 47, some 67 percent went to college and 69 percent are white. Twenty-one percent are black and almost 5 percent are Hispanic. Under Democratic Party rules, the delegate seats are divided equally among men and women, and while there are no firm quotas, state parties were encouraged to recruit enough minorities so the racial mix of the delegation roughly parallels that of the state's <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> voters Still, there was some irritation at the party's affirmative action program. `` We went from unfair to more unfair,'' said <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Povman </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> delegate from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Under the rules, a person can get the most votes and be elected by the people and yet not be selected as a delegate, not because <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> does n't want you, but because if you're a white Catholic and they have enough white Catholics, they'll pick a black whatever.'' While no floor fights are expected over the presidential nomination, credentials challenges or changes to the rules, the delegates come to town with a lot weighing on their minds. A sampling of those surveyed by the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> found that about a third of them are worried about the federal budget deficit, unemployment, foreign trade or the economy in general. Next on the list is combatting the flow of illegal drugs into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, followed by education and the twin issues of world peace and nuclear arms control. `` I have a son who would be of age to go into service,'' said <PERSON> Hilda </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourg </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> delegate from <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. `` I want to keep the nation at peace.'' Asked his opinion of the nation's No. 1 issue, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Logsdon </PERSON>, a sheriff from <LOCATION> Elizabethtown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, replied: `` As someone in law enforcement, drugs. I think we need to quit calling it a war and make it one.'' Even with few issues to be fought out and so few self-confessed politicians in attendance, politics _ that nasty business _ found its way into the process. Asked if she thought the Democrats had devised a fair way of picking delegates, <PERSON> Cyrel </PERSON> <PERSON> Foote </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> delegate from <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, complained: `` No, there's a lot of politics involved.''
</TEXT>
