 The dollar retreated against the Japanese yen today in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, while share prices topped the 28,000-point barrier in active trading on the stock exchange. The dollar started trading at 132.90 yen before peaking at 133.08 yen, its high for the day, during the morning session. It fell steadily in afternoon dealings before closing trading at 132.70 yen, down 0.63 yen from Monday's 133.33 yen. It reached a low of 132.60 yen at one point. `` The dollar is being thrown around by comments from various people in the financial circle,'' said a dealer at a major securities firm, speaking on condition of anonymity. He said the currency reacted today to a statement by a high-ranking <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> official that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is ready to tolerate a higher dollar. `` The dollar is going to be sensitive until the release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures'' scheduled for Friday, said the dealer. He added that the currency is likely to move between a range of 131-133 yen prior to the announcement. The dollar has been forced lower in the past by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade reports showing a growing imbalance of imports over exports. But recent reports have shown improvements in the trade gap and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency has stabilized. However, the dealer said sentiment in the market seemed to show that traders do not expect an improvement in the May figures. `` The last two months were good so this time it may be bad,'' he said. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues built on its 68.91-point gain registered Monday and added a further 113.85 points, or 0.40 percent, for a 28,099.84 total by the end of trading. The index last closed on the 28,000-point level on June 20 when it finished trading at 28,139.03. `` The gain was better than expected,'' said the securities dealer. `` Summer is usually a slow season for stock trading.'' Traders attributed the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> gain to activity centered on large-capital issues, including steel and heavy industrials. Volume on the first section was estimated at 1.9 billion shares, up from 1.1 billion shares Monday. `` Prices will fluctuate,'' said the dealer. `` But the market is basically strong.''
