<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Continues to Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus shrank 16 percent during the first half of 1988 as booming imports outstripped a moderate increase in exports, the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday. Analysts said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was a major beneficiary of the increased imports. The ministry said in its preliminary report <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus during the first six months of the year was $ 33.7 billion, or $ 6.4 billion less than in the first half of 1987. In June, the country had a surplus of $ 5.92 billion, down $ 668.3 million from the same month last year. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> dipped 14.9 percent, from $ 24.6 billion to $ 20.9 billion for the first half of this year compared with the same period in 1987. The ministry attributed the rapid decline in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus to the steep increase in imports, fueled by the nearly 100 percent rise in the value of the Japanese yen against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar in the last three years. The stronger yen made foreign products cheaper in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and Japanese products more expensive abroad. The rising yen boosted the country's imports by 34.3 percent to $ 91.8 billion for the first six months of 1988 on a custom-cleared basis, while exports rose 15.7 percent to $ 125.4 billion. The statistics showed American exporters, bolstered by the weak dollar, are increasing their sales in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> faster than European and Asian exporters. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest trading partner. <PERSON> Sumio </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoga </PERSON>, director of the ministry's export department, said Americans sold more office equipment, aircraft and capital goods to Japanese while Japanese automobile exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continued its downward trend. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is clearly a beneficiary of the yen appreciation,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerstenhaber </PERSON>, a senior economist with <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` American exports to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is clearly outstripping its imports from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> ... and the trend is very unlikely to change.'' Analysts see the decline in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s surplus and its increase in imports as the beginning of a long trend. `` The figures for the first six months confirmed that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is streadily heading the way to becoming an importing country,'' said <PERSON> Josen </PERSON> <PERSON> Takahashi </PERSON>, a chief analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> think tank. `` Imports are growing at much faster pace than we expected. It seems like a matter of time until <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s account marks a deficit,'' he said.
