 Grain and soybean futures opened mixed to higher today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, recovering slightly from Monday's steep losses in cautious trading ahead of an eagerly awaited crop report. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report, due out after the close, was to include revised production estimates for wheat, corn and soybeans. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> normally does not revise its springtime production estimates until August. But government experts decided to revise the figures in today's report to reflect the effects of the drought. <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Karlin </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, predicted the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> would be conservative in estimating drought damage. `` This report will be based on computer models,'' he said. `` Once you get into the August report, you have extension agents going out in the fields and doing some sample surveys.'' Prices for grain and soybean futures fell sharply Monday in reaction to weekend rains in the Corn Belt and forecasts for more showers this week. In early trading, wheat was 3 -RCB- cents to 5 \ cents higher with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.72 a bushel; corn was 1 -RCB- cents lower to 7 -RCB- cents higher with July at $ 2.96 a bushel; oats were 5 -LCB- cents lower to 11 cents higher with July at $ 2.77 a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents lower to 14 cents higher with July at $ 8.72 a bushel Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mostly higher in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle settled .37 cent lower to .25 cent higher with August at 66.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent to .55 cent lower with August at 75.70 cents a pound; hogs were .02 cent lower to .57 cent higher with July at 45.50 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .08 cent to .55 cent higher with July at 33.10 cents a pound. Cattle futures settled mostly higher on Monday while pork futures were mostly lower.
