<FIRST>s f BC-Dollar-Mergers Adv17   07-12 1147</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Mergers, Adv 17,1185</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday July 17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>For Foreign Buyers, The Exchange Rate Is No Object</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A year ago, the British mass-market jeweler <ORGANIZATION> Ratners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> spent about $ 200 million to acquire an Ohio-based jewelry company. The experience was so positive, the transaction so simple, and the rewards potentially so great, that <ORGANIZATION> Ratners </ORGANIZATION> since has snapped up two more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies. <ORGANIZATION> Ratners </ORGANIZATION> embodies a veritable 10-year tradition among the British, who are the most prolific acquirers of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses, followed by the Canadians, West Germans, French and Japanese. Those expecting to see a slowdown tied to the dollar's recent resurgence in foreign-exchange trading may be disappointed. Like a tycoon buying a fine diamond for his mistress, corporate suitors from abroad still act as if money is no object, at least not now. Last year, foreigners spent $ 40.4 billion on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> acquisitions; in the first six months of this year, the tally registered $ 21 billion by some estimates. Those involved in the deals _ from investment bankers to the purchasers themselves _ say the status of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency is of little consequence as long as it does n't really skyrocket. `` It's a commercial strategy, not the exchange rate that's going to influence us,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Coppel </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ratners </ORGANIZATION>' group finance director, from his <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> office. Since its long decline bottomed out recently, the dollar's value has risen as much as 10 percent against some major currencies. Most foreign companies with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> operations are active participants in the currency markets, buying and selling dollars as a hedge against swings in the exchange rate. W.T. <ORGANIZATION> Grimm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a Chicago-based firm that tracks mergers and acquisitions, noted that foreigners often end up paying even more for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies than American acquirers. While <PERSON> Grimm </PERSON> attributed that to their `` aggressive entry into the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market,'' investment bankers look to more practical considerations. For one thing, `` You've got a lengthier process of negotiating a contract simply because you must bring all your troops from your home country, and they're not familiar with the process,'' said <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Fabuss </PERSON>, a senior vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. In addition, foreigners often do not initiate their own, exclusive transactions. `` It's hard for them to say, ` I want company X' and go out and try to get it. They tend to appear in auction situations where the highest price wins, and currency allows them to pay slightly more,'' he added. Last year, foreign buyers announced 220 takeover deals, accounting for 11 percent of all the mergers and acquisitions in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Grimm </PERSON> reported. Nearly half of those deals carried price tags of $ 100 million or more, with the average price of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company totaling a record $ 315.4 million. Most of the takeovers occurred in the retail, chemicals and industrial equipment and machinery Among the billion-dollar deals so far this year are the British construction company <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>'s purchase of <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and Canadian investor <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>'s acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Currently under way is the sale of at least a dozen units of the <ORGANIZATION> Singer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to help finance <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON>'s purchase of the machinery and defense company A number of foreigners are bidding on those operations. Despite their willingness to pay top dollar for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> properties, foreigners are still finding some relative bargains here. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said American factories outperformed their rivals overseas last year in reducing labor costs and making their goods more competitive on world markets. Measured in devalued American dollars, labor costs in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> declined 1.5 percent in 1987, compared with increases of 7.5 percent in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, 7.7 percent in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, 13.5 p \ _ Z -RRB- ss, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> Finding an American mate takes some looking. <PERSON> Coppel </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Ratners </ORGANIZATION> began assessing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market in September 1986 and quickly realized the `` enormous potential of the $ 20 billion-a-year -LRB- jewelry -RRB- market.'' With the help of <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ratners </ORGANIZATION> zeroed in on <ORGANIZATION> Sterling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, headquartered in <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. The deal closed less than a year later. Of particular interest to <ORGANIZATION> Ratners </ORGANIZATION> was Sterling's diamond expertise. Savvy in buying raw gemstones in <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bombay </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON> has shown <ORGANIZATION> Ratners </ORGANIZATION> how to cut costs so much that <PERSON> Coppel </PERSON> predicted the company's diamond business would jump from 12 percent to 20 percent of total sales. `` Since then we've been able to acquire two other companies at a much more favorable -LRB- exchange -RRB- rate,'' <PERSON> Coppel </PERSON> said, referring to the privately held jewelers <ORGANIZATION> Osterman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Westhall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lodge </PERSON>, a professor at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s business school, said that the type of company helps determine the price foreigners are willing to pay. `` If you're coming here to acquire the latest American technology in gene-splitting, the dollar rate is not as important'' because intellectual assets are harder to value, he said. `` On the other hand, if you are coming here to set up an auto factory, then the exchange rate becomes more important.'' Political pressure has kept the technologically aggressive Japanese from bidding on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> high-tech companies, but politics may also be contributing to the foreign merger wave. `` As the politics of trade become more intense, Japanese and European companies regard a holding in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> as a protector of their access to our marketplace,'' <PERSON> Lodge </PERSON> said. As the flow of business across the oceans increases, investment banking companies have responded by paying more attention to courting overseas clients. Over the past year, <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> has opened full-service offices in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, rather than relying on small branches. <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> is looking east for growth. Employment in the company's <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> office has jumped to 400 from 290 less than two years ago. In addition, the company has established a `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> group'' in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to facilitate transactions between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Japanese businesses, a spokesman said. At <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, a new unit was established in April specifically to work on foreign direct investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The operation's 20-member staff currently has `` several major deals in the works,'' said bank spokesman <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>. While foreigners are reveling in all the dollars their currencies can buy, some of the Americans doing business with them are n't so happy. One investment banker on a recent business trip in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> complained that his $ 435-a-night room at the elegant hotel <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Crillon </PERSON> was a mere `` broom closet.'' Lamenting how few francs his dollar buys, he said, `` Why is it <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> chardonnays now make sense?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday July 17</NOTE>
