<FIRST>r f AM-EnergyEfficiency     07-12 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Energy Efficiency,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Group Urges New Push For Efficiency</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The next administration should push for new gains in energy efficiency, and without sacrifice for conscientious consumers, an advocacy group said Tuesday. Such a goal should incorporate an auto fuel-economy requirement of 45 miles per gallon, a 50-cent-per-gallon gasoline tax increase and a high `` gas-guzzler'' tax to be rebated to buyers of fuel efficient cars, said the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> for an Energy-Efficient Economy. The report, produced by a panel of environmentalists, academics and business executives, argued that abundant opportunities for efficiency gains are the best way to counter several threats at once _ acid rain, excessive dependence on imported oil, international competition and the `` greenhouse'' warming of the earth by man-made gases, notably the carbon dioxide produced by burning fossil fuels. Also Tuesday, a related report was issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Safe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, an advocacy group supported by several environmental organizations and others, arguing that nuclear power has had virtually no effect in holding down oil use `` and can not have any substantial impact in the foreseeable future.'' The communications council also argued for a 45 mpg fuel-economy standard, to be raised to 60 mpg in the year 2008. Unlike many reports advocating the pursuit of efficiency, the study by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> an </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy-Efficient </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economy </ORGANIZATION> explicitly argued that efficiency should be pursued only as long as it's cost-effective _ with environmental and balance-of-trade costs taken into account. Some of the authors told a news conference that point is a long way away. `` The opportunities are proliferating ... the marketing folks have n't been able to keep up with the engineers,'' said <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Geller </PERSON>, associate director of the council. Asked which party was more likely to be receptive to the recommendations, <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> said, `` We would hope any administration would accept this agenda and push it forward.'' `` It's been a great disaster that conservation has been associated with sitting in the dark,'' said another author, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Socolow </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. The report listed 10 improvements it considered still possible, the largest being transmissions with continuously variable gear ratios, estimated to improve efficiency by 12 percent. The second best improvement, at 8 percent, would be engines with four valves per cylinder. That design already has been incorporated in several models in the past two or three years. Cars currently must get 26 mpg, and buyers will not demand mileage above about 30 mpg because annual savings are small, the authors said. The higher standards could mean cars would cost $ 200 to $ 800 more initially, but this would be recovered over the lifetime of the car in reductions in operating costs, they said. A 50-cent tax would make sure `` consumers are given a price signal that better reflects the real cost of the resource and encourages conservation,'' and some of the $ 40 billion to $ 60 billion raised each year could be returned to the poor through income tax provisions. The tax should be imposed in increments of 10 cents per year for five years, the report said. If oil prices double, the tax should be held to 30 cents. If fuel efficiency gains are disappointing, the tax could climb higher. The gas-guzzler tax, which currently can exceed $ 2,000 for certain luxury cars, should be broadened to raise funds for rebates, perhaps $ 1,000, on fuel-efficent cars, the report said. The rebates could apply to models 50 percent better than today's best, the report said This would imply payments for cars getting about 75 mpg.
</TEXT>
