 Stock prices fell today as investors showed concern over interest rates and the trade deficit. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was off 19.74 points to 2,091.57 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street. Losers outnumbered gainers nearly 3 to 1 in the overall tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 364 up, 1,063 down and 466 unchanged. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, swelled by dividend-related trading, came to 121.54 million shares as of 2 p.m. on Wall Street. Stock market investors have dwelled lately on the possibility that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> will push up interest rates as a way to cool the economy and stave off inflation. Concerns about rising interest rates have dampened the stock market because more attractive yields on bonds could siphon money away from stocks. Also, high rates could hurt stock prices by slowing economic growth. `` This is a market that's back-pedaling,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON>, an investment strategist for <ORGANIZATION> Gruntal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` Anxiety over higher interest rates is keeping players on the sidelines as well as stalling some of the summer sizzle that appears to lie ahead.'' Traders also appeared cautious in advance of Friday's release of figures on the May merchandise trade deficit. The heaviest trading was related to dividend-capture strategies. <ORGANIZATION> Centerior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> had more than 9 million shares change hands in early trading. <ORGANIZATION> Puget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sound </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Light and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION