<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices fell Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in a spiritless session without market-moving news before the release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and British economic data later in the week. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 18.3 points, or 0.1 percent, lower at 1,858.5. On Wall Street, the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average was down 12.80 points at 2,098.51 as <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> trading drew to a close, after opening about 4 points higher. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> traders said Wall Street's wobbly performance punctuated an already declining British stock market. Dealers said the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market lacked a sense of direction and there was a lack of news to spur share prices. `` There's really so little going on,'' said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Charlesworth </PERSON>, senior dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, adding: `` a lethargy is beginning to creep into this market.'' Economic data due for release later in the week kept players cautious and sidelined. Of particular concern was Thursday's spate of British corporate earnings reports and figures on British unemployment, average earnings and industrial output, as well as Friday's release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade data for May and the British retail price index for June. Lower crude oil prices weighed down oil company shares, as takeover hopes within the sector were dashed, analysts said. Weak oil prices were beginning to `` take the steam out'' of the rampant takeover talk that has permeated the sector over recent weeks, said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaitow </PERSON>, a technical stock analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ