 Grain and soybean futures closed moderately higher Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in cautious trading ahead of an eagerly awaited crop report. `` Overall, by recent standards, it was a fairly dull session,'' said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Spilka </PERSON>, a grain analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. The rally was basically a technical rebound after three days of sharply lower prices, <PERSON> Spilka </PERSON> said. He said gains probably were limited by edginess over the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> crop report, which was released after the close. News that the report's revised production estimates for corn, soybeans and spring wheat would be based on conditions as of Tuesday instead of July 1 prompted a buying flurry early in the session, <PERSON> Spilka </PERSON> said. In the report, the agency estimated 1988 soybean production at 1.65 billion bushels, compared with a June estimate of 1.88 billion and 1987 production of 1.9 billion bushels. This year's corn harvest was estimated at 5.2 billion bushels, compared with the June estimate of 7.3 billion and year-ago production of 7.1 billion. Production of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat this year was estimated at 1.84 billion bushels, compared with the June estimate of 2.12 billion and 1987 production of 2.1 billion. At the close, wheat was 9 \ cents to 12 -RCB- cents higher with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.79 a bushel; corn was 12 \ cents to 17 \ cents higher with July at $ 3.05 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 1 -LCB- cents to 18 cents higher with July at $