<HEAD>Venezuela Postpones Payments on Bonds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> has unilaterally postponed payments on as much as $ 850 million in Republic of <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> bonds scheduled to mature this year, the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The five-year bonds, issued in 1983, will be paid between May 1990 and June 1992, according to the government's Official Gazette of June 14. The bonds had originally been scheduled to mature in June of this year. The notes subject to postponement are held by Venezuelan government entities, and their non-payment should not affect the nation's credit rating, foreign bankers in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> said. The government paid off another $ 100 million in Republic of <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> bonds maturing this year that were held by private investors, a <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> source said. The payment delay comes as the government attempts to safeguard its reserves of foreign currencies in the face of declining oil income. Finance Minister <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurtado </PERSON> has estimated that <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> will have a balance-of-payments deficit this year of around $ 4 billion. <PERSON> Hurtado </PERSON> is in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> this week for meetings with the world banking community, the ministry said. He is scheduled to meet with officials of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> InterAmerican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, and will sign a $ 71.6 million <ORGANIZATION> IADB </ORGANIZATION> credit for road repair.
