<HEAD>Eastern Rejects Pilots' Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS 5 new final grafs to UPDATE with additional pilot
reaction; No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> management was unimpressed with a four-year contract offer from its pilots, who claim they are offering $ 51.5 million a year in cost savings to the airline, an <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Tuesday. `` The arithmetic they -LRB- the pilots -RRB- used totally distorts the proposal,'' <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said. `` The main point -LRB- is -RRB- they've hit us with a proposal that would increase our costs.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s calculations have found that the pilots' proposal would increase the airline's costs by $ 116 million annually <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> added that overall, cumulative increases in the pilots' offer would raise <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s costs by 33 percent. The pilots contended that the 5 percent increases in pay, along with stock, they are requesting would be more than offset by money-saving concessions in productivity rules and vacations. `` It would give -LRB- Eastern -RRB- some form of economic relief and at the same time, protect our pilots,'' said spokesman <PERSON> J.B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> local representing about 3,500 Eastern pilots. `` We think it's very fair.'' Eastern, losing an estimated $ 1 million daily, has said it must have wage and work-rule concessions from its three unions to cut labor costs by around 30 percent overall. The pilots' current contract became amendable this month. Eastern has been in federal mediation with its largest union, the 12,000-member Machinists, for nearly seven months. The pilots' proposal was designed to halt a `` downsizing'' of Eastern that's seen a steady reduction in the number of flights. The pilots estimate that by summer's end, nearly 1,000 Eastern pilots will have left the airline since the 1986 takeover by giant <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ many because of tense labor-management relations and uncertainty about the carrier's future. The pilots' proposal would include a `` fence agreement'' keeping Eastern separate from <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, a nonunion carrier also owned by Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>. Eastern unions say <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> wants to strip Eastern of its assets. The pilots' offer also calls for three 5 percent pay increases and one 3 percent raise, plus shares in <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> stock, over the life of the proposed four-year contract. One of the most critical proposals involves payment of an unspecified amount of money to pilots who have yet to take a vacation this year, the pilots said. Pilots would receive five days of vacation and be compensated for the rest. Those pilots who have taken a vacation this year would receive an unspecified amount of cash for any remaining vacation time due them. This proposal alone would save <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> $ 11 million, according to <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said it would be cheaper to hire new pilots. `` The pilot shortage thing is a myth. We have enough pilots to fly the schedule we intend to operate,'' <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said. Under the present contract, a pilot can fly 84 hours per month. Under the proposal, that would rise to 88 hours and go as high as 90 hours under a so-called buffer provision. That provision, according to <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION>, would save the airline another $ 9.5 millon annually. But <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said the pilots want time-and-a-half for the extra hours. A third element that would make more efficient use of the pilots would save the company another $ 31 million yearly, <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said Eastern calculated the savings at only $ 6.7 million. <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON>, after hearing of <PERSON> Matell </PERSON>'s remarks, said <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> stands by its calculations. `` That's certainly not the way it prints out,'' <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON> said of Eastern's figures. `` We felt and still do that it's a very positive approach that would save the company some money,'' <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON> said, adding that the pilots' other priorities include maintaining Eastern as a large, separate airline. He said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> management has n't presented its own offer. `` They have not made a formal proposal as yet. That's just delaying the negotiations,'' said <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON>.
