<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices fell today as investors showed concern over interest rates and the trade deficit. Stock market investors have dwelled lately on the possibility that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> will push up interest rates as a way to cool the economy and stave off inflation. Concerns about rising interest rates have dampened the stock market because more attractive yields on bonds could siphon money away from stocks. Also, high rates could hurt stock prices by slowing economic growth. A rise in agricultural commodity prices raised inflation fears, which hurt the bond market, analysts said. `` This is a market that's back-pedaling,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON>, an investment strategist for <ORGANIZATION> Gruntal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` Anxiety over higher interest rates is keeping players on the sidelines as well as stalling some of the summer sizzle that appears to lie ahead.'' Traders also appeared cautious in advance of Friday's release of figures on the May merchandise trade deficit.
</TEXT>
