<HEAD>Dollar Finishes Lower; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar slipped Tuesday, as profit-taking pushed the currency lower against all major currencies except the Canadian dollar. Gold prices were mixed. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> quoted a late bid for gold of $ 436.25 as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from Monday's late bid of $ 434.50. Traders said they had expected a slight sell-off of the dollar, which rose to recent highs against several major currencies on Monday despite concerted central bank intervention. Concern that the central banks might step in again to sell dollars may have kept the currency from climbing, analysts said. The dollar's slow, measured decline began early in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and then continued when trading shifted to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the currency settled at the lows of the day. But traders said bullish sentiment surrounding the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency remains intact. `` The dollar has n't dropped very far _ there's still very good demand in the market,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON>, an assistant vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` People are re-examining what's ahead of us and squaring up their positions,'' he said, referring to the government's report on the nation's May trade deficit, which is due out Friday The consensus is that the May report will register about $ 11 billion, up from the $ 9.9 billion deficit reported for April, which was the lowest imbalance in three years. In the past, the dollar has plunged in response to an unexpected widening of the trade gap and soared when it narrowed. But <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Sloane </PERSON>, a currency analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, noted that the trade numbers were more of an obsession earlier in the year. `` The dollar has made big moves without the trade numbers, and the trend to a much stronger dollar has become much more visible in the last few months,'' he said. <PERSON> Sloane </PERSON> said the dollar might be influenced by comments by <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, who is scheduled to testify before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on monetary policy Thursday. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 0.63 Japanese yen to a closing 132.70 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was slightly lower at 132.63 yen. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 132.51 yen, down from 133.07 yen on Monday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound closed at $ 1.6960, up from $ 1.6900 late Monday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, it cost $ 1.6970 to buy one pound, more expensive than Monday's $ 1.6925. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late rates Monday, included: 1.8365 West German marks, down from 1.8423; 1.5187 Swiss francs, down from 1.5305; 6.1970 French francs, down from 6.2065; 1,361.75 Italian lire, down from 1,367.25, and 1.2103 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2072. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Monday: 1.8376 West German marks, down from 1.8460; 1.5235 Swiss francs, down from 1.5350; 6.1940 French francs, down from 6.2080; 2.0745 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0750; 1,363.25 Italian lire, down from 1,364.50, and 1.2100 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2080. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, one troy ounce of gold cost $ 437, up from $ 434.60 on Monday. In <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, gold closed in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a late bid of $ 436.50 a troy ounce, up from $ 435.10 late Monday. But in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 2 to a bid of $ 433.50 a troy ounce. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 4.41 to close at a bid $ 437.63. Silver bullion rose on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex to $ 6.974 a troy ounce from $ 6.937 on Monday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> the metal finished at a bid price of $ 6.91 a troy ounce, down from $ 6.94 bid late Monday.
