<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Prices Rise in Advance of Crop Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices moved moderately higher Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in cautious dealings ahead of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s eagerly awaited monthly crop report. Analysts said the report, released after trading ended and forecasting a 24 percent decline in overall <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain production, should send prices higher when trading resumes on Wednesday. But they say weather forecasts will continue to dominate the markets. On other markets, livestock and meat futures were mixed; energy futures were mixed; precious metals were higher and stock-index futures retreated. Grain analysts called the crop report bullish for soybean prices, bearish for corn and slightly bearish for wheat. But the anticipated strength in soybeans was expected to offset the weakness in the grains, ultimately pulling all the grain markets higher Wednesday _ at least for a few minutes. `` After about three minutes of trading, they'll have worked off their report anxiety and we'll be looking at Friday's, Saturday's and Sunday's weather, which we see as hot, hot, hot,'' said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Spilka </PERSON>, a grain analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` I do n't think the market's going to dwell on this report too long,'' agreed <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Karlin </PERSON>, chief research analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Based on conditions as of Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> predicted a 27 percent drop in corn production from 1987, a 14 percent drop in soybean production, and a wheat crop 13 percent smaller than that harvested last year. The corn harvest was estimated at 5.2 billion bushels, compared with the June estimate of 7.3 billion and year-ago production of 7.06 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> estimated 1988 soybean production at 1.65 billion bushels, compared with a June estimate of 1.88 billion and 1987 production of 1.9 billion bushels. Production of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat was projected at 1.84 billion bushels, compared with the June estimate of 2.12 billion and 1987 production of 2.1 billion. Analysts called the corn and wheat estimates conservative. `` This just confirms everybody's opinion that there's some crop damage out there, and the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> is looking at a bit more of a problem in soybeans than the trade had anticipated,'' <PERSON> Spilka </PERSON> said. This year's planted soybean acreage, estimated by the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> at 58.52 million acres, was about 700,000 acres below market expectations. Planted corn acreage, estimated at 67.52 million acres, was about 500,000 acres more than expected. Grain and soybean futures advanced moderately ahead of the report, which was issued after the markets closed. Wheat settled 8 -RCB- cents to 13 \ cents higher with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.81 \ a bushel; corn was 8 \ cents to 17 -RCB- cents higher with July at $ 3.06 a bushel; oats were 1 -LCB- cents lower to 15 cents higher with July at $ 2.79 a bushel; soybeans were 7 cents to 21 -LCB- cents higher with July at $ 8.79 -LCB- Cattle futures finished mixed while some pork futures advanced their daily limits on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in reaction to the rise in feed grain prices, said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Durchholz </PERSON>, a pork-market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> AgriVisor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>. Traders expect livestock and meat prices to rise sharply next year after falling in the near term due to widespread producer selling of animals this summer because of the drought-driven rise in feed prices, he said The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> also reported the worst July 1 pasture conditions in history, which should encourage further drought-pattern trading on the livestock markets, said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Sterling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analytical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>. Live cattle settled .70 cent lower to .17 cent higher with August at 65.82 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .60 cent lower with August at 75.72 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent to the limit 1.50 cents higher with July at 45.67 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .40 cent to the limit 2 cents higher with July at 33.10 cents a pound Crude oil prices weakened in volatile trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, but unleaded gasoline strengthened because of tight supplies and speculation about higher <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> demand, analysts said. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents to 17 cents lower with August at $ 14.72 a barrel; heating oil was .15 cent to .68 cent lower with August at 40.65 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .06 cent lower to 1.35 cents higher with August at 53.48 cents a gallon. Precious metals futures posted modest gains on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange due to the inflationary implications of higher grain prices and a weaker dollar Gold settled $ 2 to $ 2.30 higher with August at $ 438.70 a troy ounce; silver was 3.7 cents to 3.8 cents higher with July at $ 6.974 a troy ounce. Stock-index futures retreated on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the contract for September delivery of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 index settled 3.10 points lower at 269.35.
