<FIRST>r f AM-Bentsen-Labor     07-12 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bentsen-Labor,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bentsen Receives Praise from Labor Despite Poor Union Rating</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also mocving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> has the worst lifetime voting record on labor issues of any of the running mates <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was considering, according to an <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> rating. Nevertheless, union lobbyists on Tuesday were quick to praise the Democratic choice. The <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrat was hailed for his role in salvaging labor's top legislative priority this year _ making companies give workers 60 days advance notice before closing their plants or laying them off `` <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was extremely helpful in recognizing that the two _ plant closing notices and the trade bill _ were compatible,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McGlotten </PERSON>, the 14.1-million-member labor federation's legislative director `` And he let his colleagues know how he felt.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last week passed with a veto-proof 72-vote majority legislation requiring companies to provide 60 days advance notice of plant closings or layoffs involving more than 50 people. The House is expected to follow suit on Wednesday. Labor leaders demanded enactment of the mandatory layoff notices as the price for maintaining their support for a massive overhauling of the nation's trade laws that <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was a key player in crafting as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> vetoed the trade bill in May, citing the layoff notices that were then a part of it as his primary reason. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Booe </PERSON>, secretary-treasurer of the <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, and a member of the Democrats' platform-drafting committee, acknowledged that <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was not labor's main spear carrier on the trade and plant closing issues. `` But he did n't do a lot of the things that he could have done to mess us up, and there were a lot of other people urging him to,'' said <PERSON> Booe </PERSON>. `` I do n't think you can call him a labor hero, but he's been on our side more than he's been against us.'' As a three-term senator from a right-to-work state where less than 12 percent of the workers belong to unions, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> has always walked a fine line between conservative businessmen and labor activists in the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Despite a lifetime voting record of only 51 percent on labor issues, according to the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> labor leaders endorsed his re-election in 1982. All of the five other members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> who <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was considering as possible running mates have stronger COPE voting records. Another southerner, Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, had the highest _ 88 percent. But <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was listed as voting `` right'' on eight of 10 issues in 1987 that the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> considered in compiling its rankings, shoring up his support among labor leaders. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s only wrong votes were on raising the threshold on government construction contracts for which union-scale wages must be paid and giving employers who hire illegal aliens extensions before fining them. `` He's been all over the map,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerekes </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Work </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, a group that advocates state laws like the one in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> which outlaws labor contracts that require non-members to pay dues to unions that represent them. Earlier this year, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> came out against a so-called double-breasting bill that is the top priority of construction unions. The bill would prohibit unionized companies from operating non-union subsidiaries as a means of getting around wage and other provisions of labor contracts they've signed. But last month he voted against a measure to make violence on picket lines a federal crime, a reversal of his vote two years ago favoring such legislation. <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> members hold 751 of the 4,161 delegates at the Democratic convention opening next week in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. Combined with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associations </ORGANIZATION>' 280 delegates, about one-fourth of total that will nominate <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> come from the labor movement. `` Obviously, we would like to see somebody who had a 100 percent voting record,'' said <PERSON> McGlotten </PERSON>. `` But as you review things, a COPE record becomes less important than whether someone's door is open to us and understands our problems. He understands our problems.''
