<HEAD>Steelmakers' Costs Up Because of Drought, But Orders May Be Cut
Later</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GARY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The steel industry faces a possible reduction in orders as the drought reduces harvests and cuts the demand for new farm equipment, industry representatives said Tuesday. The drought also has increased operating costs by forcing steelmakers to contract for smaller, lighter ore barge loads that can navigate shallower waters near the <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> ore ranges. Steelmakers add, however, the drought likely will not harm the industry's recovery and the generally strong market for steel. <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Works </PERSON> produces tin-plated steel, among other products, for the canning industry, and <ORGANIZATION> Inland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates a facility in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, supplies steel to farm machinery manufacturers. `` There's some talk that canners, if the crops are lower, will be canning less, and that could have an effect on shipment,'' said <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuebler </PERSON>. `` Harvest time is still down the road for a lot of crops yet, so we do n't see any impact.'' An Inland newsletter said the company anticipates some customers might cut back on orders if the drought continues. `` Farm equipment manufacturers, in particular, may be hurt by declining sales of tractors and combines,'' the newsletter said. Inland spokesman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Nekvasil </PERSON> said some companies that depend on river traffic stalled by drought-lowered waters may reduce steel orders if they ca n't move their own finished products to market. <PERSON> Kuebler </PERSON> said smaller ore loads increase shipping costs by about 10 percent. That has not yet translated into an increase in steel prices, he said. Nevertheless, orders for steel remain strong, said <PERSON> Nekvasil </PERSON>. `` We continue to see business conditions strong,'' he said. `` I certainly would n't see anything that would threaten recovery or profitability. There's a very strong market for steel today.''
