<FIRST>u f AM-Drought-Congress 1stLd-Writethru f0242 07-12 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0242,0813</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Unveil Disaster Bill as Lyng Warns of `Mammoth' Drought</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 13th graf pvs bgng, `A 50 cent,' with 1 graf to CLARIFY
that reduction was per hundredweight</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawmakers unveiled a wide-ranging relief bill for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s drought-stricken farmers Tuesday, promising payments of up to $ 100,000 to keep them on the land despite the withering heat and lack of rain. The legislation is expected to move quickly through <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The chairmen of both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Agriculture committees vowed to move as rapidly as possible and <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said that because of the extent of the drought, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration will overlook minor flaws in the bill and support the measure. `` This is the largest drought that our nation has ever experienced,'' <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> declared as senators met to start committee action on the disaster legislation. `` I think history will show that it's truly more mammoth than any of us has ever experienced,'' <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said. He said a recurrence next year would `` suggest that we've done something wrong and the Gods are against us.'' Lawmakers did not give an estimate of the cost of the relief legislation but expressed their resolve not to allow drought to set off a rash of bankruptcies in the countryside, just as the farm economy is shaking off the painful stagnation of the early 1980s. `` We're not going to allow their lives as farmers and ranchers to end because of a freak of nature,'' <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., said Both the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Agriculture committees opened hearings on the bill on Tuesday. The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel, Rep. E. `` Kika'' de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said it `` would send the wrong signal'' to leave the job unfinished in August when lawmakers flee <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s heat. He added that he was hopeful the panel could dispense with any parade of witnesses from farm lobbies and instead act this week on any changes congressmen want to make in the draft bill. Senate Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., also called for `` quick action'' on the legislation because the `` American farmer needs help It's that simple.'' `` We must make certain that our relief package is targeted to those who need the help,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said in a statement. `` There can be no windfalls for any individual or group. We owe that much to the farmers and the taxpayers.'' <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> was briefing <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members on the long, hot dry spell when aides arrived from the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> five blocks away with a fresh forecast that the drought would cut this year's corn output to around 5.2 billion bushels, down from 7.06 billion last year. Under the proposed legislation, disaster payments would be capped at $ 100,000 for each individual farmer. Payments would represent 65 percent of pre-drought expected earnings, whether from target prices, price-support loans or market prices. But they would apply only to losses in excess of 35 percent of the crop. A 50 cent reduction per hundredweight in dairy price supports scheduled to start next year would be canceled under the legislation. Dairymen say such an action is warranted by skyrocketing feed costs, although it was one of their prime goals long before the drought set in. Government emergency feed programs already in effect would be overhauled and made available to a broader range of farmers. The drought has burned away a considerable amount of hay and thus put feed at a premium. Wheat, feed grains, cotton and rice producers would not be required to refund to the government any deficiency payments they have received in advance. The income-support payments represent the difference between the market value of their harvest and its value at higher, so-called target prices set by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> under the 1985 farm program and adjusted annually by the secretary of agriculture. Market prices have climbed steadily closer to target prices in anticipation of a diminished harvest, and thus the drought has reduced federal income-support payments as well. The drying up of these subsidies at a time when farmers have fewer crops to take to market threatens to hurt some of them. To complicate matters, many farmers have received 40 percent of their deficiency payments from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> in advance and will have to refund a portion of them unless rescued by relief legislation. Another key provision would help farmers convert from production of corn, cotton and a variety of other crops to soybean production without paying certain financial penalties under the farm program. The provision is being closely watched in the farm and segments of the financial communities because soybeans are expected to be in short supply as a result of the drought and prices already are soaring.
</TEXT>
