<HEAD>USG Settles Lawsuit Against Merrill Lynch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it had reached an out-of-court settlement of its 2-month-old lawsuit charging <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> with attempting to profit from the illegal use of confidential information. USG, the country's leading producer of gypsum wallboard and other building materials, would not reveal the terms of the agreement. The lawsuit, filed May 3 in U.S. District Court in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, stemmed from <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION>'s involvement in an attempted hostile takeover of USG by <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> L.P. </ORGANIZATION>, a partnership headed by oilmen <PERSON> Cyril </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Midland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. USG had accused the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment house of providing <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> with confidential information acquired while <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> served as <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION>'s financial adviser in prior business deals. <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> denied any conflict in its involvement with <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>, which withdrew its takeover bid on June 9 after losing a proxy fight for six seats on <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors. <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> was one of <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>' financial advisers in its takeover attempt and had committed $ 200 million of its own money to assist in the proposed takeover.
