<HEAD>Harvard Business School To Require Ethics Course This Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Honesty and fairness will be in the curriculum at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> starting this fall, when all students entering the graduate school will be required to take a three-week course in ethics. After the Wall Street insider trading scandal broke in 1986, the nation's business schools, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> included, were criticized for not stressing ethics in their teachings of future business managers. `` We want to send a signal early on that these issues are important to the organization,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Piper </PERSON>, one of the professors who will teach the course at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, said in Tuesday's editions of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Piper </PERSON> defined the teaching of ethics as instilling the values of respect, honesty, trust and fairness and said the key was to show that ethics are part of the decision-making process for managers. The ungraded course will begin the second week of the term. The school also plans to have more discussion of ethics in its regular courses and has hired research assistants to develop material. Workshops will be held for faculty members. Fewer than 10 percent of business schools require students to take ethics, according to ethics specialist <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Bentley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> received $ 20 million from former <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Shad </PERSON> for the teaching of ethics. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s critics, including some faculty members, had questioned the school's commitment to teaching ethics. Some critics suggested at the time of Shad's gift that <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> got interested in the subject only when it got the money. The school countered that ethics already were taught in many of its regular courses and a separate course was not needed. <PERSON> Piper </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> that after one year of study, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> decided on a dual approach _ a separate mini-course and more discussion of ethics in other courses. He said ethics always had been taught at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> but may have been squeezed out over time. Interest in doing more came before the Wall Street scandal, he said, but the scandal made people realize `` that the pendulum may have swung too far.'' Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Bok </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> he did not think professors at the business school `` are able to put ethics into their courses at the level they should.'' `` There is a dangerous tendency on the part of some people to say that ethics is something we all know about,'' <PERSON> Bok </PERSON> said.
